2018/02/06/manufacturing-industry/ How will Brexit affect the UK's manufacturing industry?] UK Trade Policy Observatory, February 2018\n* [https://www.civilservant.org.uk/library/2018-Ivan_Rogers-the_real_post-Brexit_options.pdf The real post-Brexit options] Lecture by Ivan Rogers at the University of Glasgow, 23 May 2018\n* [https://ukandeu.ac.uk/explainers/what-are-the-options-for-the-uks-trading-relationship-with-the-eu-after-brexit/ What are the options for the UK's trading relationship with the EU after Brexit?] UK in a Changing Europe, King's College London, December 2018\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/brexit-phrasebook-a-guide-to-the-talks-key-terms Brexit phrasebook: a guide to the talks' key terms] The Guardian, 23 November 2018\n* [https://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2019/03/lord-ashcroft-how-the-united-kingdom-voted-on-eu-referendum-day-and-why.html ''Lord Ashcroft: How the United Kingdom voted on EU referendum day \u2013 and why''] Conservative Home, 17 March 2019\n* [https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa/eu/brexit/keydocuments/Omnibus-Bill-Memo.pdf Explanatory Memorandum for the ''Withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union (Consequential Provisions) Bill 2019'' introduced by the Irish government in the legislature ([[Oireachtas]])]\n* [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=OJ%3AL%3A2019%3A080I%3AFULL&from=EN EU Council decision, 22 March 2019, extending the negotiating period]\n\n'''Relating to court cases'''\n* [http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKSC/2017/5.html Judgment] of the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] in ''[[R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]''\n* [http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?text=&docid=208636&pageIndex=0&doclang=en&mode=lst&dir=&occ=first&part=1&cid=1085843 Judgment] of the [[European Court of Justice]] in the Wightman case: Right of unilateral revocation of the notification\n* ''[[Wilson v Prime Minister]]'' [2018] [https://www.ukineuchallenge.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/260395-Judgment-10.12.2018-Version-for-publication.pdf EWHC 3520 (Admin)]\n* Ewan McGaughey [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09615768.2018.1555881 ''Could Brexit be Void?''] King's Law Journal, Volume 29, 2018, Issue 3\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/IDAN/2017/599352/EPRS_IDA(2017)599352_EN.pdf ''UK withdrawal from the European Union: Legal and procedural issues''] European Parliamentary Research Service, March 2017\n* Ronan McCrea [https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/brexit/2018/12/20/the-legal-issues-of-revoking-the-notification-to-leave-the-eu-but-then-notifying-to-leave-again/ ''The legal issues of revoking the notification to leave the EU \u2013 but then notifying to leave again''] London School of Economics, 20 December 2018\n\n{{United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016|state=expanded}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Brexit| ]]\n[[Category:2010s in politics]]\n[[Category:2016 in British politics]]\n[[Category:Consequences of the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]\n[[Category:English words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom and the European Union]]\n[[Category:Withdrawal from the European Union]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Portmanteaus]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\n{{short description|United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{brexit sidebar}}\n{{United Kingdom in the European Union}}\n\n'''Brexit''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|\u025b|k|s|\u026a|t|,_|\u02c8|b|r|\u025b|g|z|\u026a|t}};<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Damien|title='Breksit' or 'bregzit'? The question that divides a nation|url=https://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|date=11 August 2017|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704035541/http://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> a [[portmanteau]] of \"British\" and \"exit\") is the [[Withdrawal from the European Union|withdrawal]] of the [[United Kingdom]] (UK) from the [[European Union]] (EU). Following a UK-wide [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum in June 2016]], in which 52% voted to leave and 48% voted to remain in the EU, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] formally announced the country's withdrawal in March 2017, beginning the [[Brexit negotiations|Brexit process]]. The withdrawal was delayed by deadlock in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]]. Following a general election, Parliament [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|ratified]] the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]], and the UK left the EU at 11&nbsp;p.m. [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] on 31 January 2020. This began a transition period that is set to end on 31 December 2020, during which the UK and EU will negotiate their future relationship.<ref name=Bennett>{{Cite news|title=How will the Brexit transition period work?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|newspaper=Telegraph|date=27 January 2020|author=Asa Bennett|access-date=28 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128044559/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK remains subject to [[European Union law|EU law]] and remains part of the EU [[European Union Customs Union|customs union]] and [[European Single Market|single market]] during the transition, but is no longer part of the EU's political bodies or institutions.<ref name=Edgington>{{cite news|author=Tom Edgington|title=Brexit: What is the transition period?|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|date=31 January 2020|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131215049/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=QAEC>{{cite news|publisher=European Commission|date=24 January 2020|title=Questions and Answers on the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union on 31 January 2020|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201003034/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nWithdrawal was advocated by [[Euroscepticism#Hard Euroscepticism|hard Eurosceptics]] and some [[Euroscepticism#Soft Euroscepticism|soft Eurosceptics]] and opposed by [[Pro-Europeanism|pro-Europeanists]] and other soft Eurosceptics, with both sides of the argument spanning the political spectrum. The UK [[Accession of the United Kingdom to the European Communities|joined]] the [[European Communities]] (EC) \u2013 principally the [[European Economic Community]] (EEC) \u2013 in 1973, and its continued membership was endorsed in a [[1975 United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum|1975 referendum]]. In the 1970s and 1980s, withdrawal from the EC was advocated mainly by the political left, e.g. in the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]'s 1983 election manifesto. The 1992 [[Maastricht Treaty]] founded the EU, but was not put to a referendum. The Eurosceptic wing of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] led a [[Maastricht Rebels|rebellion]] over ratification of the treaty and, with the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) and the cross-party [[People's Pledge]] campaign, pressured the Conservative [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]] [[David Cameron]] to hold a [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]] on continued EU membership, which was held in June 2016. Cameron, who had campaigned to remain, resigned after the result and was succeeded by [[Theresa May]].\n\nOn 29 March 2017, the UK government formally began the withdrawal process by [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoking Article 50]] of the [[Treaty on European Union]] with [[European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Act 2017|permission from Parliament]]. May called a [[2017 United Kingdom general election|snap general election]] in June 2017, which resulted in a Conservative minority government [[Confidence and supply|supported]] by the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP). UK\u2013EU [[Brexit negotiations|withdrawal negotiations]] began later that month. The UK negotiated to leave the EU customs union and single market. This resulted in the November 2018 [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]], but the British parliament [[Parliamentary votes on Brexit|voted against ratifying it]] three times. The Labour Party wanted any agreement to maintain a customs union, while many Conservatives opposed the agreement's [[Brexit divorce bill|financial settlement]], as well as the \"[[Irish backstop]]\" designed to prevent border controls between [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]]. The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP), and others sought to reverse Brexit through a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|proposed second referendum]].\n\nIn March 2019, the British parliament voted for May to ask the EU to delay Brexit until April, and then later October. Having failed to get her agreement approved, May resigned as Prime Minister in July and was succeeded by [[Boris Johnson]]. He sought to replace parts of the agreement and vowed to leave the EU by the new deadline. On 17 October 2019, the British government and the EU agreed on a revised withdrawal agreement, with new arrangements for Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_withdrawal_agreement_including_protocol_on_ireland_and_nothern_ireland.pdf|title=Revised Withdrawal Agreement|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|website=|publisher=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017103006/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_withdrawal_agreement_including_protocol_on_ireland_and_nothern_ireland.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50079385|title=New Brexit deal agreed, says Boris Johnson|date=17 October 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213193556/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50079385|archive-date=13 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Parliament approved the agreement for further scrutiny, but rejected passing it into law before the 31 October deadline, and forced the government (through the \"[[European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019|Benn Act]]\") to ask for a third Brexit delay. An [[2019 United Kingdom general election|early general election]] was then held on 12 December. The Conservatives won a large majority in that election, with Johnson declaring that the UK would leave the EU in early 2020.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Mark|last1=Landler|first2=Stephen|last2=Castle|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/conservatives-headed-for-commanding-majority-in-uk-vote-brexit-will-happen/ar-AAK4vR4?ocid=spartanntp|title=Conservatives Win Commanding Majority in U.K. Vote: 'Brexit Will Happen'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|via=[[MSN]]|date=12 December 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213060550/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/conservatives-headed-for-commanding-majority-in-uk-vote-brexit-will-happen/ar-AAK4vR4%3Focid%3Dspartanntp|archive-date=13 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The withdrawal agreement was ratified by the UK on 23 January and by the EU on 30 January; it came into force on 31 January.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement|title=Boris Johnson signs Brexit withdrawal agreement|last1=Boffey|first1=Daniel|last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|date=24 January 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124122448/https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement|archive-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"sparrow1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/jan/29/pmqs-boris-johnson-corbyn-warned-he-faces-first-commons-revolt-since-election-over-huawei-live-news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|title=Brexit: MEPs approve withdrawal agreement after emotional debate and claims UK will return - live news|work=The Guardian|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129232319/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/jan/29/pmqs-boris-johnson-corbyn-warned-he-faces-first-commons-revolt-since-election-over-huawei-live-news|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51333314|title=Brexit: UK leaves the European Union|work=BBC News|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131232236/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51333314|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMany [[Impact of Brexit|effects of Brexit]] depend on how closely the UK will be tied to the EU, or whether the transition period ends without terms being agreed (a \"[[no-deal Brexit]]\").<ref name=Edgington/> The broad consensus among economists is that Brexit will likely harm the UK's economy and reduce its real [[per capita income]] in the long term, and that the referendum itself damaged the economy.{{#tag:ref|See:<ref name=\"NYT Feel Good\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/22/business/international/brexit-referendum-eu-economy.html|title='Brexit,' a Feel-Good Vote That Could Sink Britain's Economy|last=Goodman|first=Peter S.|date=20 May 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=28 November 2017|issn=0362-4331|quote=finding economists who say they believe that a Brexit will spur the British economy is like looking for a doctor who thinks forswearing vegetables is the key to a long life|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044816/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/22/business/international/brexit-referendum-eu-economy.html|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://voxeu.org/content/brexit-beckons-thinking-ahead-leading-economists|title=Brexit Beckons: Thinking ahead by leading economists|last=Baldwin|first=Richard|date=31 July 2016|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=22 November 2017|quote=On 23 June 2016, 52% of British voters decided that being the first country ever to leave the EU was a price worth paying for 'taking back control', despite advice from economists clearly showing that Brexit would make the UK 'permanently poorer' (HM Treasury 2016). The extent of agreement among economists on the costs of Brexit was extraordinary: forecast after forecast supported similar conclusions (which have so far proved accurate in the aftermath of the Brexit vote).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125093912/http://voxeu.org/content/brexit-beckons-thinking-ahead-leading-economists|archive-date=25 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/brexit-ii|title=Brexit survey|publisher=[[Initiative on Global Markets]], University of Chicago|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017213942/http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/brexit-ii|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/brexit-2|title=Brexit survey II|publisher=[[Initiative on Global Markets]], University of Chicago|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304001918/http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/brexit-2|archive-date=4 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/28/economists-reject-brexit-boost-cameron|title=Economists overwhelmingly reject Brexit in boost for Cameron|last=Sodha|first=Sonia|date=28 May 2016|work=The Observer|access-date=1 November 2017|last2=Helm|first2=Toby|issn=0029-7712|last3=Inman|first3=Phillip|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112444/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/28/economists-reject-brexit-boost-cameron|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c2b0359e-d0dc-11e6-b06b-680c49b4b4c0|title=Most economists still pessimistic about effects of Brexit|website=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722161150/https://www.ft.com/content/c2b0359e-d0dc-11e6-b06b-680c49b4b4c0|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/dc62922a-204b-11e7-a454-ab04428977f9|title=Brexit will damage UK standards of living, say economists|website=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=22 November 2017|quote=Unlike the short-term effects of Brexit, which have been better than most had predicted, most economists say the ultimate impact of leaving the EU still appears likely to be more negative than positive. But the one thing almost all agree upon is that no one will know how big the effects are for some time.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722161152/https://www.ft.com/content/dc62922a-204b-11e7-a454-ab04428977f9|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/why-is-the-academic-consensus-on-the-cost-of-brexit-being-ignored-59540|title=Why is the academic consensus on the cost of Brexit being ignored?|last=Wren-Lewis|first=Simon|work=The Conversation|access-date=22 November 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040705/https://theconversation.com/why-is-the-academic-consensus-on-the-cost-of-brexit-being-ignored-59540|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-22/brexit-s-fallout-on-u-k-economy-seen-as-chronic-not-crippling|title=Brexit to Hit Jobs, Wealth and Output for Years to Come, Economists Say|date=22 February 2017|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=22 November 2017|quote=\"The U.K. economy may be paying for Brexit for a long time to come{{nbsp}}... It won't mean Armageddon, but the broad consensus among economists\u2014whose predictions about the initial fallout were largely too pessimistic\u2014is for a prolonged effect that will ultimately diminish output, jobs and wealth to some degree.\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722162650/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-22/brexit-s-fallout-on-u-k-economy-seen-as-chronic-not-crippling|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":12mitchell\">{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Paul|last2=Mitchell|first2=Ian|date=1 March 2017|title=The Brexit vote, economics, and economic policy|journal=Oxford Review of Economic Policy|volume=33|issue=suppl_1|pages=S12\u2013S21|doi=10.1093/oxrep/grx017|issn=0266-903X}}</ref><ref name=\"auto12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21727078-patrick-minford-thinks-gdp-could-increase-68-most-economists-say-brexit-will-hurt|title=Most economists say Brexit will hurt the economy\u2014but one disagrees|work=The Economist|access-date=22 November 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030213649/https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21727078-patrick-minford-thinks-gdp-could-increase-68-most-economists-say-brexit-will-hurt|archive-date=30 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/uk-economic-forecast-brexit-reason-economy-living-standards-wage-loss-households-city-a8072436.html|title=This is the real reason the UK's economic forecasts look so bad|date=23 November 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=28 November 2017|quote=One thing economists do generally agree on is that leaving the European Union and putting new trade barriers between Britain and our largest and closest trading partners is extremely unlikely to boost UK productivity growth\u2014and is far more likely to slow it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722161839/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/uk-economic-forecast-brexit-reason-economy-living-standards-wage-loss-households-city-a8072436.html|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} However, the inaccuracy of pre-referendum forecasts has been criticised by the [[chief economist]] at the [[Bank of England]].<ref>{{cite web|author=6 January 2017 at 4:41am |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2017-01-06/bank-of-england-economist-brexit-forecasts-criticism-is-fair-cop/ |title='Michael Fish moment' as UK economy thrives after Brexit vote - ITV News |publisher=Itv.com |date=2017-01-06 |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref> Brexit is likely to reduce immigration from [[European Economic Area]] (EEA) countries to the UK, and poses challenges for UK higher education, academic research and security. Following Brexit, [[European Union law|EU law]] and the [[Court of Justice of the European Union|EU Court of Justice]] no longer have [[Primacy of European Union law|supremacy over UK laws]] or its [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]], except to a temporary extent. The ''[[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]]'' retains relevant EU law as [[Law of the United Kingdom|domestic law]], which the UK could then amend or repeal.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{main|Timeline of Brexit}}\n\n==Terminology and etymology==\n{{main|Glossary of Brexit terms}}\n\nIn the wake of the referendum of 23 June 2016, many new pieces of Brexit-related [[jargon]] entered popular use.<ref>Al Jazeera. (2018). [https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/12/brexit-jargon-backstop-deal-17-key-terms-explained-181201182945771.html ''Brexit jargon: From backstop to no deal, 17 key terms explained'' (Al Jazeera)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522100618/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/12/brexit-jargon-backstop-deal-17-key-terms-explained-181201182945771.html |date=22 May 2019 }}. Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref><ref>BBC. (2019). [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43470987 ''Brexit: Jargon-busting guide to the key terms'' (BBC)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907110157/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43470987 |date=7 September 2019 }}. Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Background: the United Kingdom and Europe==\n{{Main|History of European Union\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\n[[File:Inner Six and Outer Seven.svg|thumb|250px|left|The [[Inner Six]] (blue) and [[Outer Seven]] (green) of [[European integration]] in 1961]]\n\nThe \"[[Inner Six]]\" European countries signed the [[Treaty of Paris (1951)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1951, establishing the [[European Coal and Steel Community]] (ECSC). The 1955 [[Messina Conference]] deemed that the ECSC was a success, and resolved to extend the concept further, thereby leading to the 1957 [[Treaties of Rome]] establishing the [[European Economic Community]] (EEC) and the [[European Atomic Energy Community]] (Euratom). In [[Merger Treaty|1967,]] these became known as the European Communities (EC). The UK attempted to join in 1963 and 1967, but these applications were vetoed by the [[President of France]], [[Charles de Gaulle]].<ref>{{cite news|title=1967: De Gaulle says \"non\" to Britain \u2013 again|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/27/newsid_4187000/4187714.stm|work=BBC News|date=27 November 1976|accessdate=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202044425/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/27/newsid_4187000/4187714.stm|archive-date=2 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome time after de Gaulle resigned in 1969, the UK successfully applied for [[European Communities|EC]] membership, and the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] prime minister [[Edward Heath]] signed the [[Treaty of Accession 1972|Treaty of Accession]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/transformingsociety/tradeindustry/importexport/overview/europe/|title=Into Europe|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=25 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328231317/https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/transformingsociety/tradeindustry/importexport/overview/europe/|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Parliament passed the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|European Communities Act]] later that year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://treaties.fco.gov.uk/docs/fullnames/pdf/1979/TS0018%20(1979)%20CMND-7463%201972%2022%20JAN,%20BRUSSELS%3B%20TREATY%20CONCERNING%20ACCESSION%20OF%20DENMARK%20IRELAND%20NORWAY%20UK%20&%20NI%20TO%20EEC%20&%20EAEC_1.pdf|title=English text of EU Accession Treaty 1972, Cmnd. 7463|accessdate=24 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221025512/http://treaties.fco.gov.uk/docs/fullnames/pdf/1979/TS0018%20%281979%29%20CMND-7463%201972%2022%20JAN%2C%20BRUSSELS%3B%20TREATY%20CONCERNING%20ACCESSION%20OF%20DENMARK%20IRELAND%20NORWAY%20UK%20%26%20NI%20TO%20EEC%20%26%20EAEC_1.pdf |archive-date=21 December 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and the UK joined Denmark and Ireland in [[Accession of the United Kingdom to the European Communities|becoming a member]] on 1 January 1973.<ref>{{cite news|title=1973: Britain joins the EEC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/1/newsid_2459000/2459167.stm|work=BBC News|date=1 January 1973|accessdate=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114142111/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/1/newsid_2459000/2459167.stm|archive-date=14 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe opposition [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] won the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]] without a majority and then contested the subsequent [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]] with a commitment to renegotiate Britain's terms of membership of the EC, believing them to be unfavourable, and then hold a [[referendum]] on whether to remain in the EC on the new terms.<ref>Alex May, ''Britain and Europe since 1945'' (1999).</ref> Labour again won the election (this time with a small majority), and in 1975 the UK held its [[1975 United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum|first ever national referendum]], asking whether the UK should remain in the EC. Despite significant division within the ruling Labour Party,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/26/newsid_2503000/2503155.stm|title=BBC on this day \u2013 26 \u2013 1975: Labour votes to leave the EEC|publisher=BBC|access-date=20 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212151032/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/26/newsid_2503000/2503155.stm|archive-date=12 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> all major political parties and the mainstream press supported continuing membership of the EC. On 5 June 1975, 67.2% of the electorate and all but two<ref>the [[Shetland Islands]] and the [[Outer Hebrides]]</ref> UK counties and regions voted to stay in;<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7253#fullreport|title=Research Briefings \u2013 The 1974\u20131975 UK Renegotiation of EEC Membership and Referendum|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=19 May 2016|date=13 July 2015|last1=Miller|first1=Vaughne|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426013801/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7253#fullreport|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> support for the UK to leave the EC in 1975 appears unrelated to the support for Leave in the 2016 referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trfetzer.com/who-voted-for-brexit/|title=Who Voted for Brexit? A comprehensive district level analysis|publisher=Becker, Fetzer, Novy, University of Warwick|accessdate=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401145148/http://www.trfetzer.com/who-voted-for-brexit/|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum, 1975 compared to United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016.svg|400px|thumb|right|Comparison of results of 1975 and 2016 referendums]]\n\nThe Labour Party campaigned in the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] on a commitment to withdraw from the EC without a referendum.<ref name=\"foot\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/8550425.stm|title=Michael Foot: What did the \"longest suicide note\" say?|first=Rajini|last=Vaidyanathan|work=BBC News|date=4 March 2010|accessdate=21 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902193702/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/8550425.stm|archive-date=2 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After their heavy defeat in that election, Labour changed its policy.<ref name=\"foot\" /> In 1985, the [[Second Thatcher ministry|second Margaret Thatcher government]] ratified the [[Single European Act]]\u2014the first major revision to the [[Treaty of Rome]]\u2014without a referendum.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn October 1990, under pressure from senior ministers and despite Thatcher's deep reservations, the UK joined the [[European Exchange Rate Mechanism]] (ERM), with the [[pound sterling]] pegged to the [[Deutsche Mark|deutschmark]]. Thatcher resigned as Prime Minister the following month, amid Conservative Party divisions arising partly from her increasingly Eurosceptic views. The UK and Italy were forced to withdraw from the ERM in September 1992, after the pound sterling and the lira came under pressure from [[currency speculation]] (\"[[Black Wednesday]]\").<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dury|first1=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|title=Black Wednesday|url=http://is.muni.cz/el/1456/podzim2011/MPF_AFIN/um/27608616/27608949/Black_Wednesday.pdf|accessdate=24 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001135346/https://is.muni.cz/el/1456/podzim2011/MPF_AFIN/um/27608616/27608949/Black_Wednesday.pdf|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUnder the Maastricht Treaty, the EC became the EU on 1 November 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://europa.eu/european-union/eu-law/decision-making/treaties_en|title=EU treaties|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=15 September 2016 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913032647/http://europa.eu/european-union/eu-law/decision-making/treaties_en|archivedate=13 September 2016}}</ref> reflecting the evolution of the organisation from an [[economic union]] into a [[political union|political one]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/about-eu/basic-information/about/index_en.htm|title=EUROPA The EU in brief|publisher=Europa (web portal)|accessdate=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726054654/http://europa.eu/about-eu/basic-information/about/index_en.htm|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Denmark]], [[France]], and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] held referendums to ratify the Maastricht Treaty. In accordance with [[Constitution of the United Kingdom|British constitutional convention]], specifically that of [[parliamentary sovereignty]], ratification in the UK was not subject to approval by referendum. Despite this, British constitutional historian [[Vernon Bogdanor]] wrote that there was \"a clear constitutional rationale for requiring a referendum\" because although MPs are entrusted with legislative power by the electorate, they are not given authority to transfer that power (the UK's previous three referendums all concerned this). Further, as the ratification of the treaty was in the manifestos of the three major political parties, voters opposed to ratification had no way to express it. For Bogdanor, while the ratification by the House of Commons might be legal, it would not be legitimate\u2014which requires popular consent. The way in which the treaty was ratified, he judged, was \"likely to have fundamental consequences both for British politics and for Britain's relationship with the [EC].\"<ref>Bogdanor also quotes [[John Locke]]'s ''[[Two Treatises of Government|The Second Treatise of Government]]'': 'The Legislative cannot transfer the power of making laws to any other hands. For it being but a delegated power from the People, they who have it cannot pass it to others.' \u2013 Bogdanor, Vernon (8 June 1993). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/why-the-people-should-have-a-vote-on-maastricht-the-house-of-lords-must-uphold-democracy-and-insist-1490346.html Why the people should have a vote on Maastricht: The House of Lords must uphold democracy and insist on a referendum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629035411/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/why-the-people-should-have-a-vote-on-maastricht-the-house-of-lords-must-uphold-democracy-and-insist-1490346.html |date=29 June 2019 }}. ''[[The Independent]]''.</ref><ref>Bogdanor, Vernon (26 July 1993). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/futility-of-a-house-with-no-windows-1487252.html Futility of a House with no windows] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708155618/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/futility-of-a-house-with-no-windows-1487252.html |date=8 July 2019 }}. ''The Independent''.</ref> This perceived [[democratic deficit]] directly led to the formation of the [[Referendum Party]] and the [[United Kingdom Independence Party|UK Independence Party]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n====Rising Euroscepticism====\n{{Main|Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom}}\n{{multiple image\n | border = infobox\n | image_gap = 20\n | caption_align = center\n| align = right\n| total_width = 400\n| image1 = Margaret Thatcher cropped2.png\n| alt1 = Margaret Thatcher\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = Nigel Farage (45718080574) (cropped).jpg\n| alt2 = Nigel Farage\n| caption2 =\n| image3 = David Cameron official.jpg\n| alt3 = David Cameron\n| caption3 =\n| footer = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] prime ministers [[Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher]] (''left''{{--)}} and [[David Cameron|Cameron]] (''right''{{--)}} used [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] rhetoric while being in favour of the UK's membership and the development of the [[European Single Market]]. Euroscepticism\u2014and in particular the impact of the [[UK Independence Party]] (''former leader [[Nigel Farage|Farage]] pictured centre''{{--)}} on the Conservatives' election results\u2014contributed to Cameron's [[2015\u201316 United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership|2015 attempt to renegotiate the UK's EU membership]] and ultimately the holding of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].\n}}\n\nThatcher, who had previously supported the common market and the Single European Act, in the [[Bruges speech]] of 1988 warned against \"a European super-state exercising a new dominance from Brussels\".{{cn|date=February 2020}} She influenced [[Daniel Hannan]], who in 1990 founded the Oxford Campaign for Independent Britain; \"With hindsight, some see this as the start of the campaign for Brexit\", the ''[[Financial Times]]'' later wrote.<ref name=\"kuper20190620\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2|title=How Oxford university shaped Brexit \u2013 and Britain's next prime minister|last=Kuper|first=Simon|date=20 June 2019|work=Financial Times|access-date=21 June 2019|language=en-GB|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621101919/https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1994, [[Sir James Goldsmith]] formed the Referendum Party to contest the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] on a platform of providing a referendum on the nature of the UK's relationship with the rest of the EU.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heath|first=Anthony|last2=Jowell|first2=Roger|last3=Taylor|first3=Bridget|last4=Thomson|first4=Katarina|date=1 January 1998|title=Euroscepticism and the referendum party|journal=British Elections & Parties Review|volume=8|issue=1|pages=95\u2013110|doi=10.1080/13689889808413007|issn=1368-9886}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carter|first=N.|last2=Evans|first2=M.|last3=Alderman|first3=K.|last4=Gorham|first4=S.|date=1 July 1998|title=Europe, Goldsmith and the Referendum Party|journal=Parliamentary Affairs|volume=51|issue=3|pages=470\u2013485|doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.pa.a028811|issn=0031-2290}}</ref> The party fielded candidates in 547 constituencies at that election, and won 810,860 votes\u20142.6% of the total votes cast<ref name=\"ref party\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge97/partycand.htm|title=UK Election 1997|publisher=Politicsresources.net|accessdate=16 July 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921035222/http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge97/partycand.htm|archivedate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\u2014but failed to win a parliamentary seat because the vote was spread across the country. The Referendum Party disbanded after Goldsmith's death in 1997.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP), a Eurosceptic political party, was formed in 1993. It achieved third place in the UK during the [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2004 European elections]], second place in the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2009 European elections]] and first place in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European elections]], with 27.5% of the total vote. This was the first time since the [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910 general election]] that any party other than Labour or the Conservatives had taken the largest share of the vote in a nationwide election.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 key lessons from the European election results|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/26/10-key-lessons-european-election-results|work=The Guardian|date=26 May 2014|accessdate=31 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402054604/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/26/10-key-lessons-european-election-results|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> UKIP's electoral success in the 2014 European election is documented as the strongest correlate of the support for the Leave campaign in the 2016 referendum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Migration Cause Extreme Voting?|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/research/centres/cage/manage/publications/306-2016_becker_fetzer.pdf|work=Becker and Fetzer, University of Warwick|date=18 October 2016|accessdate=30 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114083425/http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/research/centres/cage/manage/publications/306-2016_becker_fetzer.pdf|archive-date=14 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUKIP won two by-elections (triggered by defecting Conservative MPs) in 2014; in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], the party took 12.6% of the total vote and held [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|one of the two seats won in 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2015/may/07/live-uk-election-results-in-full|title=2015 UK general election results in full|author=Matt Osborn|work=The Guardian|date=7 May 2015|access-date=11 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402042953/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2015/may/07/live-uk-election-results-in-full|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Opinion polls 1977\u20132015====\n{{Main|Opinion polling for the United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\n\nBoth pro- and anti-EU views had majority support at different times from 1977 to 2015.<ref name=\"Mortimore\">{{Cite news|url=http://theconversation.com/polling-history-40-years-of-british-views-on-in-or-out-of-europe-61250|title=Polling history: 40 years of British views on \"in or out\" of Europe|last=Mortimore|first=Roger|newspaper=The Conversation|access-date=25 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403145856/https://theconversation.com/polling-history-40-years-of-british-views-on-in-or-out-of-europe-61250|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[1975 United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum|EC membership referendum of 1975]], two-thirds of British voters favoured continued EC membership. Over the decades of UK-EU membership, Euroscepticism existed on both the left and right of British politics.<ref>Gifford, Chris. ''The Making of Eurosceptic Britain''. Ashgate Publishing, 2014. pp. 55, 68</ref><ref name=\"Foster\">Foster, Anthony. ''Euroscepticism in Contemporary British Politics: Opposition to Europe in the Conservative and Labour Parties since 1945''. Routledge, 2003. pp. 68\u201369</ref><ref>Taylor, Graham. ''Understanding Brexit: Why Britain Voted to Leave the European Union''. Emerald Group Publishing, 2017. p. 91. Quote: \"The coalition that came together to secure Brexit, however, included a diverse range of individuals, groups and interests. [...] There were also supporters of Brexit on the left{{nbsp}}...\"</ref>\n\nAccording to a statistical analysis published in April 2016 by Professor [[John Curtice]] of [[Strathclyde University]], surveys showed an increase in Euroscepticism (defined as a wish to sever or reduce the powers of the EU) from 38% in 1993 to 65% in 2015. The BSA survey for the period of July\u2013November 2015 showed that 60% backed the option to continue as a member and 30% backed withdrawal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarran|first=Brian|date=8 April 2016|title=The Economy: a Brexit vote winner?|journal=Significance|volume=13|issue=2|pages=6\u20137|doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2016.00891.x}}</ref>\n\n==Referendum of 2016==\n{{Main|2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\n\n===Negotiations for membership reform===\n{{Main|United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership, 2015\u201316}}\n\nIn 2012, Prime Minister David Cameron initially rejected calls for a referendum on the UK's EU membership,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron defies Tory right over EU referendum: Prime minister, buoyed by successful negotiations on eurozone banking reform, rejects \"in or out\" referendum on EU|author=Nicholas Watt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jun/29/cameron-no-eu-referendum|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=2 July 2012|quote=David Cameron placed himself on a collision course with the Tory right when he mounted a passionate defence of Britain's membership of the EU and rejected out of hand an \"in or out\" referendum.|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226053945/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jun/29/cameron-no-eu-referendum|archive-date=26 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> but then suggested the possibility of a future referendum to endorse his proposed renegotiation of Britain's relationship with the rest of the EU.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM accused of weak stance on Europe referendum|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jul/01/david-cameron-europe-referendum-noncommittal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 July 2012|accessdate=2 July 2012|quote=Cameron said he would continue to work for \"a different, more flexible and less onerous position for Britain within the EU\".|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604094602/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jul/01/david-cameron-europe-referendum-noncommittal|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[BBC]], \"The prime minister acknowledged the need to ensure the UK's [renegotiated] position within the [EU] had 'the full-hearted support of the British people' but they needed to show 'tactical and strategic patience'.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18659072|title=David Cameron 'prepared to consider EU referendum'|date=1 July 2012|work=BBC News|quote=Mr Cameron said{{nbsp}}... he would 'continue to work for a different, more flexible and less onerous position for Britain within the EU'.|accessdate=2 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702020639/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18659072|archive-date=2 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 January 2013, under pressure from many of his MPs and from the rise of UKIP, Cameron announced in his [[Bloomberg speech]] that a Conservative government would hold an in-or-out referendum on EU membership before the end of 2017, on a renegotiated package, if elected in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|7 May 2015 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21148282|title=David Cameron promises in/out referendum on EU|work=BBC News|date=23 January 2013|accessdate=23 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020146/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21148282|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This was included in the Conservative Party manifesto for the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-32302062|title=At-a-glance: Conservative manifesto|date=15 April 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=21 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403121018/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-32302062|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/14/conservatives-election-manifesto-2015-the-key-points|title=Conservatives election manifesto 2015 \u2013 the key points|first=Frances|last=Perraudin|date=14 April 2015|website=the Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402084711/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/14/conservatives-election-manifesto-2015-the-key-points|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservative Party won the election with a majority. Soon afterwards, the [[European Union Referendum Act 2015]] was introduced into Parliament to enable the referendum. Cameron favoured remaining in a reformed EU, and sought to renegotiate on four key points: protection of the single market for non-eurozone countries, reduction of \"red tape\", exempting Britain from \"ever-closer union\", and restricting immigration from the rest of the EU.<ref name=\"BBC News Nov 2015\">{{cite news|title=David Cameron sets out EU reform goals|work=BBC News|date=11 November 2015|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34770875|accessdate=16 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402180734/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34770875|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, opinion polls showed a clear majority in favour of remaining in the EU; they also showed support would drop if Cameron did not negotiate adequate safeguards{{Definition needed|What kind of 'safeguards'?|date=April 2019}} for non-eurozone member states, and restrictions on benefits for non-British EU citizens.<ref>[http://openeurope.org.uk/today/blog/new-open-europecomres-poll-failure-to-win-key-reforms-could-swing-uks-eu-referendum-vote ''New Open Europe/ComRes poll: Failure to win key reforms could swing UK's EU referendum vote''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615190602/https://openeurope.org.uk/today/blog/new-open-europecomres-poll-failure-to-win-key-reforms-could-swing-uks-eu-referendum-vote/ |date=15 June 2018 }} openeurope.org, 16 December 2015.</ref>\n\nThe outcome of the renegotiations was announced in February 2016. Some limits to in-work benefits for new EU immigrants were agreed, but before they could be applied, a member state such as the UK would have to get permission from the [[European Commission]] and then from the [[European Council]], which is composed of the heads of government of every member state.<ref name=\"FF1\">{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/europe/explaining-eu-deal-emergency-brake|first=Eleanore|last=Spaventa|title=Explaining the EU deal: the \"emergency brake\"|accessdate=25 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183814/https://fullfact.org/europe/explaining-eu-deal-emergency-brake/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech to the House of Commons on 22 February 2016, Cameron announced a referendum date of 23 June 2016, and commented on the renegotiation settlement.<ref name=\"Hansard 22 February 2016 Column 21-25\">{{cite web|title=Prime Minister sets out legal framework for EU withdrawal|website=UK Parliament|date=22 February 2016|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160222/debtext/160222-0001.htm#16022210000001|accessdate=29 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215050849/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160222/debtext/160222-0001.htm#16022210000001|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He spoke of an intention to trigger the Article 50 process immediately following a Leave vote and of the \"two-year time period to negotiate the arrangements for exit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504216/The_process_for_withdrawing_from_the_EU_print_ready.pdf|title=The process for withdrawing from the European Union|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224014248/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504216/The_process_for_withdrawing_from_the_EU_print_ready.pdf|archive-date=24 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the original wording for the referendum question was challenged,<ref name=\"Three years since the Brexit vote, meet the man behind Leave and Remain\">{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2019-06-23/three-years-since-the-brexit-vote-meet-the-man-behind-leave-and-remain|title=Three years since the Brexit vote, meet the man behind Leave and Remain|work=ITV News|date=23 June 2019|accessdate=25 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625033043/https://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2019-06-23/three-years-since-the-brexit-vote-meet-the-man-behind-leave-and-remain/|archive-date=25 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the government agreed to change the official referendum question to \"Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?\"\n\n===Referendum result===\n{{Main|Results of the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\n\nThe result was announced on the morning of 24 June: 51.89% voted in favour of leaving the EU (Leave), and 48.11% voted in favour of remaining a member of the EU (Remain).<ref name=\"BBC24forecast\">{{cite news|title=EU referendum: BBC forecasts UK votes to leave|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|work=BBC News|accessdate=24 June 2016|date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724232549/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://election.news.sky.com/referendum|title=EU Referendum Results|publisher=Sky (United Kingdom)|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160624063333/http://election.news.sky.com/referendum|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After the result was declared, Cameron announced that he would resign by October.<ref name=cameronquit>{{cite news|accessdate=24 June 2016|work=BBC News|date=24 June 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|title=Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724232549/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He stood down on 13 July 2016, with Theresa May becoming Prime Minister after a [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership contest]]. A [[EU Referendum Rules triggering a 2nd EU Referendum|petition calling for a second referendum]] attracted more than four million signatures,<ref>{{cite news|first=Christopher|last=Hooton|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-petition-for-second-eu-referendum-so-popular-the-government-sites-crashing-a7099996.html|title=Brexit: Petition for second EU referendum so popular the government site's crashing|newspaper=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726082136/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-petition-for-second-eu-referendum-so-popular-the-government-sites-crashing-a7099996.html|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Adam|last=Boult|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/24/petition-for-second-eu-referendum-attracts-thousands-of-signatur/|title=Petition for second EU referendum attracts thousands of signatures|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 June 2016|accessdate=26 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624191630/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/24/petition-for-second-eu-referendum-attracts-thousands-of-signatur/|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> but was rejected by the government on 9 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36754376|title=Brexit: Petition for second EU referendum rejected|date=9 July 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=9 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726002830/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36754376|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{UKEU2016Results}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | border = infobox\n | image_gap = 20\n | caption_align = center\n |align = centre\n |image1 = United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 voting regions results.svg\n |width1 = 250\n |image2 = United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results 2-tone.svg\n |width2 = 260\n |footer = Results by [[Country of the United Kingdom]]/region of England (left) and by council district (GB) & UK Parliament constituency (NI) (right)<br />\n{{legend|#0069b5|Leave}}\n{{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}\n}}\n\n===Voter demographics and trends===\n{{further|Causes of the vote in favour of Brexit}}\n\nA 2017 study published in ''[[Economic Policy (journal)|Economic Policy]]'' showed that the Leave vote tended to be greater in areas which had lower incomes and high [[unemployment]], a strong tradition of [[manufacturing]] employment, and in which the population had fewer [[Qualification types in the United Kingdom|qualifications]]. It also tended to be greater where there was a large flow of Eastern European migrants (mainly low-skilled workers) into areas with a large share of native low-skilled workers.<ref name=\"Becker-Fetzer-Novy\">Sascha O Becker, Thiemo Fetzer, Dennis Novy. [[doi:10.1093/epolic/eix012|\"Who voted for Brexit? A comprehensive district-level analysis\"]]. ''Economic Policy'', Volume 32, Issue 92, 1 October 2017, pp. 601\u2013650. Quotes: \"We find that fundamental characteristics of the voting population were key drivers of the Vote Leave share, in particular, their education profiles, their historical dependence on manufacturing employment as well as low income and high unemployment. At the much finer level of wards within cities, we find that areas with deprivation in terms of education, income and employment were more likely to vote Leave. [...] A larger flow of migrants from Eastern Europe reaching a local authority area with a larger share of unqualified people or a larger share of manufacturing workers is also associated with a larger Vote Leave share\".</ref> Those in lower [[NRS social grade|social grades]] (especially the '[[working class]]') were more likely to vote Leave, while those in higher social grades (especially the '[[upper middle class]]') more likely to vote Remain.<ref>Noel Dempsey & Neil Johnston. [http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7501/CBP-7501.pdf \"Political disengagement in the UK: who is disengaged?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329195051/https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7501/CBP-7501.pdf |date=29 March 2019 }}. [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] briefing paper. House of Commons Library, 14 September 2018. pp. 25-26</ref><ref name=\"Hobolt\">{{Cite journal|last=Hobolt|first=Sara B.|date=20 October 2016|title=The Brexit vote: a divided nation, a divided continent|journal=Journal of European Public Policy|volume=23|issue=9|pages=1259\u20131277|doi=10.1080/13501763.2016.1225785|issn=1350-1763|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/67546/7/Hobolt_The%20Brexit%20vote%20a%20divided%20.pdf|access-date=4 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006145434/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/67546/7/Hobolt_The%20Brexit%20vote%20a%20divided%20.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Becker|first=Sascha O.|last2=Fetzer|first2=Thiemo|last3=Novy|first3=Dennis|date=1 October 2017|title=Who voted for Brexit? A comprehensive district-level analysis|journal=Economic Policy|language=en|volume=32|issue=92|pages=601\u2013650|doi=10.1093/epolic/eix012|issn=0266-4658}}</ref> Studies found that the Leave vote tended to be higher in areas affected by economic decline,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carreras|first=Miguel|date=1 December 2019|title='What do we have to lose?': Local economic decline, prospect theory, and support for Brexit|journal=Electoral Studies|volume=62|page=102094|doi=10.1016/j.electstud.2019.102094|issn=0261-3794}}</ref> high rates of suicides and drug-related deaths,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koltai|first=Jonathan|last2=Varchetta|first2=Francesco Maria|last3=McKee|first3=Martin|last4=Stuckler|first4=David|title=Deaths of Despair and Brexit Votes: Cross-Local Authority Statistical Analysis in England and Wales|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=110|issue=3|pages=e1\u2013e6|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2019.305488|pmid=31855481|issn=0090-0036|year=2020}}</ref> and [[austerity]] reforms introduced in 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fetzer|first=Thiemo|date=2019|title=Did Austerity Cause Brexit?|journal=American Economic Review|language=en|volume=109|issue=11|pages=3849\u20133886|doi=10.1257/aer.20181164|issn=0002-8282}}</ref>\n\nStudies suggest that older people were more likely to vote Leave, and younger people more likely to vote Remain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/b8d097b0-3ad4-4dd9-aa25-af6374292de0|title=The truth about young people and Brexit|last=Spratt|first=Vicky|date=26 September 2018|publisher=BBC Three|language=en-GB|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125041738/https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/b8d097b0-3ad4-4dd9-aa25-af6374292de0|archive-date=25 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Thomas Sampson, an economist at the [[London School of Economics]], \"Older and less-educated voters were more likely to vote 'leave' [...] A majority of white voters wanted to leave, but only 33% of Asian voters and 27% of black voters chose leave. There was no gender split in the vote [...] Leaving the European Union received support from across the political spectrum [...] Voting to leave the European Union was strongly associated with holding socially conservative political beliefs, opposing cosmopolitanism, and thinking life in Britain is getting worse\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Sampson|first=Thomas|year=2017|title=Brexit: The Economics of International Disintegration|url=http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/dp1499.pdf|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=31|issue=4|pages=163\u2013184|doi=10.1257/jep.31.4.163|issn=0895-3309|quote=The results I summarize in this section focus on long-run effects and have a forecast horizon of 10 or more years after Brexit occurs. Less is known about the likely dynamics of the transition process or the extent to which economic uncertainty and anticipation effects will impact the economies of the United Kingdom or the European Union in advance of Brexit.|access-date=20 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214033313/http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/dp1499.pdf|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOpinion polls found that Leave voters believed leaving the EU was \"more likely to bring about a better immigration system, improved border controls, a fairer welfare system, better quality of life, and the ability to control our own laws\", while Remain voters believed EU membership \"would be better for the economy, international investment, and the UK's influence in the world\". Polls found that the main reasons people voted Leave were \"the principle that decisions about the UK should be taken in the UK\", and that leaving \"offered the best chance for the UK to regain control over immigration and its own borders\". The main reason people voted Remain was that \"the risks of voting to leave the EU looked too great when it came to things like the economy, jobs and prices\".<ref>[http://lordashcroftpolls.com/2016/06/how-the-united-kingdom-voted-and-why/ \"How the United Kingdom voted on Thursday{{nbsp}}... and why\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401203252/http://lordashcroftpolls.com/2016/06/how-the-united-kingdom-voted-and-why/ |date=1 April 2019 }}. Lord Ashcroft Polls. 24 June 2016.</ref>\n\n==Withdrawal process==\n{{Further|Withdrawal from the European Union}}{{wikisource|Consolidated version of the Treaty on European Union/Title VI: Final Provisions#Article 50|Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union}}Withdrawal from the European Union is governed by Article 50 of the [[Treaty on European Union]]. It was originally drafted by [[Lord Kerr of Kinlochard]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-design-dictators-not-uk-eu-european-lisbon-treaty-author-lord-kerr-a7655891.html|title=Article 50 was designed for European dictators, not the UK, says man who wrote it|last=Kentish|first=Benjamin|date=29 March 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229205359/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-design-dictators-not-uk-eu-european-lisbon-treaty-author-lord-kerr-a7655891.html|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> and introduced by the [[Treaty of Lisbon]] at the insistence of the United Kingdom.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} The article states that any member state can withdraw \"in accordance with its own constitutional requirements\" by notifying the [[European Council]] of its intention to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/article-50-brexit-debate-britain-eu|title=What is article 50 and why is it so central to the Brexit debate?|last=Rankin|first=Jennifer|date=25 June 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Borger|first2=Julian|last3=Rice-Oxley|first3=Mark|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229105344/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/article-50-brexit-debate-britain-eu|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> The notification triggers a two year negotiation period, in which the EU must \"negotiate and conclude an agreement with [the leaving] State, setting out the arrangements for its withdrawal, taking account of the framework for its future relationship with the [European] Union\".<ref name=\"constunit\" /> If no agreement is reached within the two years, the membership ends without an agreement, unless an extensions is unanimous agreement between all EU states, including the withdrawing one.<ref name=\"constunit\" /> On the EU side, the agreement needs to be ratified by [[Voting in the Council of the European Union|qualified majority in the European Council]], and by the European Parliament.<ref name=\"constunit\" />\n\n===Invocation of Article 50===\n{{Main|United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union}}\n[[File:Prime Minister\u2019s letter to Donald Tusk triggering Article 50.pdf|thumb|upright|Letter from Theresa May invoking Article 50]]The 2015 Referendum Act did not expressly require Article 50 to be invoked,<ref name=\"constunit\">{{cite web|url=https://constitution-unit.com/2016/01/19/what-happens-if-we-vote-for-brexit/|title=What happens if we vote for Brexit?|last=Renwick|first=Alan|date=19 January 2016|website=The Constitution Unit Blog|access-date=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731162921/https://constitution-unit.com/2016/01/19/what-happens-if-we-vote-for-brexit/|archive-date=31 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> but prior to the referendum, the UK government said it would respect the result.<ref>In a leaflet sent out before the referendum, the UK government stated \"This is your decision. The Government will implement what you decide.\" {{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/515068/why-the-government-believes-that-voting-to-remain-in-the-european-union-is-the-best-decision-for-the-uk.pdf|title=Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK. The EU referendum, Thursday, 23 June 2016.|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324214934/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/515068/why-the-government-believes-that-voting-to-remain-in-the-european-union-is-the-best-decision-for-the-uk.pdf|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> When Cameron resigned following the referendum, he said that it would be for the incoming prime minister to invoke Article 50.<ref name=cameronquit/><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Charlie|date=27 June 2016|title=David Cameron rules out second EU referendum after Brexit|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-what-is-eu-referendum-petition-david-cameron-a7105596.html|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|access-date=27 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616105002/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-what-is-eu-referendum-petition-david-cameron-a7105596.html|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The new prime minister, Theresa May, said she would wait until 2017 to invoke the article, in order to prepare for the negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/angela-merkel-backs-theresa-mays-plan-not-to-trigger-brexit-this-year|title=Angela Merkel backs Theresa May's plan not to trigger Brexit this year|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=20 July 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Oltermann|first2=Philip|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720232931/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/angela-merkel-backs-theresa-mays-plan-not-to-trigger-brexit-this-year|archive-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, she said UK would trigger Article 50 in March 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/theresa-may-to-begin-brexit-process-by-end-of-march/|title=Theresa May to begin Brexit process by end of March|last=Spence|first=Alex|date=2 October 2016|work=Politico|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229190204/https://www.politico.eu/article/theresa-may-to-begin-brexit-process-by-end-of-march/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> and in December she gained the support of MP's for her timetable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/british-mps-back-theresa-mays-brexit-timetable/|title=British MPs back Theresa May's Brexit timetable|last=Cooper|first=Charlie|date=9 December 2016|work=Politico|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229190203/https://www.politico.eu/article/british-mps-back-theresa-mays-brexit-timetable/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the UK Supreme Court ruled in [[R (Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|the Miller case]] that government could only invoke Article 50 if authorised by an act of parliament to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowcott|first1=Owen|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|last3=Asthana|first3=Anushka|title=Supreme court rules parliament must have vote to trigger article 50|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/24/supreme-court-brexit-ruling-parliament-vote-article-50|accessdate=9 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527033524/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/24/supreme-court-brexit-ruling-parliament-vote-article-50|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The government subsequently introduced a bill for that purpose, and it was passed into law on 16 March as the [[European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Act 2017]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/16/queen-give-royal-assent-article-50-bill-clearing-way-theresa/|title=Queen gives royal assent to Article 50 Bill, clearing way for Theresa May to start European Union exit talks|last=|first=|date=16 March 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229192010/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/16/queen-give-royal-assent-article-50-bill-clearing-way-theresa/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> On 29 March, Theresa May triggered Article 50 when [[Tim Barrow]], the UK's ambassador to the EU, delivered the invocation letter to European Council President [[Donald Tusk]]. This made 29 March 2019 the expected date that UK would leave EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353|title=Article 50: UK set to formally trigger Brexit process|last=|first=|date=29 March 2017|publisher=BBC|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727021653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353|archive-date=27 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39431428|title='No turning back' on Brexit as Article 50 triggered|date=30 March 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727023251/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39431428|archive-date=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the [[European Court of Justice]] (ECJ) ruled that the UK could unilaterally revoke its notification of withdrawal, as long as it was still a member and had not agreed a withdrawal agreement. The decision to do so should be \"unequivocal and unconditional\" and \"follow a democratic process\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-46481643|title=Brexit ruling: UK can cancel decision, EU court says|date=10 December 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103035740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-46481643|archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> If UK revoked their notification, they would remain a member of the EU under their current membership terms. The case was launched by Scottish politicians, and referred to the ECJ by the Scottish [[Court of Session]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ukandeu.ac.uk/revoking-article-50-after-the-ecjs-ruling/|title=Revoking Article 50 after the ECJ's ruling|last=Taylor|first=Robert|date=11 December 2018|work=The UK in a Changing Europe|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Wilson|first2=Adelyn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710143108/https://ukandeu.ac.uk/revoking-article-50-after-the-ecjs-ruling/|archive-date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===UK\u2013EU negotiations in 2017 and 2018===\n{{Main|Brexit negotiations}}\n\nPrior to the negotiations, May said that the UK government would not seek permanent [[British membership of the European Economic Area|single market membership]], would end ECJ jurisdiction, seek a new trade agreement, end [[Freedom of movement|free movement of people]] and maintain the [[Common Travel Area]] with [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-governments-negotiating-objectives-for-exiting-the-eu-pm-speech|title=The government's negotiating objectives for exiting the EU: PM speech|date=17 January 2017|publisher=Gov.uk|access-date=24 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122234703/https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-governments-negotiating-objectives-for-exiting-the-eu-pm-speech|archive-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The EU had adopted its [[European Union negotiating directives for Brexit|negotiating directives]] in May,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2017/05/22-brexit-negotiating-directives/|title=Council (Art 50) authorises the start of Brexit talks and adopts negotiating directives \u2013 Consilium|publisher=Europa (web portal)|access-date=23 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928145943/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2017/05/22-brexit-negotiating-directives/|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and appointed [[Michel Barnier|Michael Barnier]] as Chief Negotiator.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks \"Brexit: UK caves in to EU demand to agree divorce bill before trade talks\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620101013/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks |date=20 June 2019 }}, ''The Guardian'', 19 June 2017. Retrieved 20 June 2017</ref> The EU wished to perform the negotiations in two phases:  first the UK would agree to a financial commitment and to lifelong benefits for EU citizens in Britain, and then negotiations on a future relationship could begin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/|title=EU Brexit guidelines: What's in the document, and what it really means|last=Foster|first=Peter|date=29 April 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402033538/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the first phase, the member states would demand that the UK pay a \"[[Brexit divorce bill|divorce bill]]\", initially estimated as amounting to \u00a352 billion.<ref>\"Divorce settlement or leaving the club? A breakdown of the Brexit bill\" March 2017, [http://bruegel.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/WP_2017_03-.pdf A breakdown of the Brexit bill (2017)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709094307/http://bruegel.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/WP_2017_03-.pdf |date=9 July 2018 }}</ref> EU negotiators said that an agreement must be reached between UK and the EU by October 2018.<ref name=\"brexitoct18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2017-09-22/the-latest-protests-in-florence-as-uk-leader-may-speaks|title=The Latest: EU's Brexit Chief Welcomes 'Constructive' Speech|website=USNews.com|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330233432/https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2017-09-22/the-latest-protests-in-florence-as-uk-leader-may-speaks|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Theresa May called a [[2017 United Kingdom general election|snap general election, held on 8 June,]] in an attempt to \"strengthen [her] hand\" in the negotiations;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-british-vote-brexit-negotiations-could-be-delayed/2017/06/09/1a2fee88-4c9b-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html|title=After shocking British vote result, Europe ponders fate of Brexit negotiations|last=McAuley|first=James|date=9 June 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229230200/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-british-vote-brexit-negotiations-could-be-delayed/2017/06/09/1a2fee88-4c9b-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref>  but the election resulted in a hung parliament, the Conservatives losing their majority. May remained as prime minister, as on 26 June she formed [[Second May ministry|a minority government]] with a [[confidence and supply]] agreement with the [[Democratic Unionist Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40245514|title=Theresa May and the DUP deal: What you need to know|last=Hunt|first=Alex|date=26 June 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626230416/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40245514|archive-date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNegotiations commenced on 19 June 2017.<ref name=\"Guardian-uk-caves\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks|title=Brexit: UK caves in to EU demand to agree divorce bill before trade talks|last=Roberts|first=Dan|date=20 June 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 September 2017|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620101013/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Negotiating groups were established for three topics: the rights of EU citizens living in Britain and vice versa; Britain's outstanding financial obligations to the EU; and the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.<ref name=\":28\">{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/eu-uk-art-50-terms-reference_agreed_amends_en.pdf|title=Terms of Reference for the Article 50 TEU negotiations|last=|first=|date=19 June 2017|website=European Commission|access-date=29 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829213212/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/eu-uk-art-50-terms-reference_agreed_amends_en.pdf|archive-date=29 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8017|title=Brexit: the talks begin|date=12 July 2017|publisher=House of Commons Library|accessdate=20 August 2017|last1=Walker|first1=Nigel|last2=McGuinness|first2=Terry|last3=Keen|first3=Richard|last4=Hinson|first4=Suzanna|last5=Curtis|first5=John|last6=Miller|first6=Vaughne|last7=Lang|first7=Arabella|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820203409/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8017|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/06/22/let-the-brussels-games-begin|title=Let the Brussels games begin|accessdate=22 September 2018|publisher=Economist.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923052143/https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/06/22/let-the-brussels-games-begin|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2017, a partial agreement was reached. It ensured that there would be no hard border in Ireland, protected the rights of UK citizens in EU and EU citizens in UK, and estimated the financial settlement to be \u00a335\u201339 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-breakthrough-may-pledges-no-hard-border-as-commission-says-sufficient-progress-made-1.3320030|title=Brexit breakthrough: May pledges 'no hard border' as commission says 'sufficient progress' made|date=8 December 2017|newspaper=The Irish Times|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> May stressed that \"Nothing is agreed until everything is agreed\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/11/theresa-may-tell-ireland-nothing-agreed-terms-brexit-row-deal/|title=Theresa May to tell Ireland 'nothing is agreed' on terms of Brexit as row over deal intensifies|last=Hope|first=Christopher|date=11 December 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=18 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017235503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/11/theresa-may-tell-ireland-nothing-agreed-terms-brexit-row-deal/|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this partial agreement, EU leaders agreed to move on to the second phase in the negotiations:  discussion of the future relationship, a transition period and a possible trade deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/15/brexit-talks-eu-next-phase-brussels-theresa-may|title=EU leaders agree Brexit talks can move on to phase two|last=Boffey|first=Daniel|date=15 December 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017235504/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/15/brexit-talks-eu-next-phase-brussels-theresa-may|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, a 21-month transition period and the terms for it were provisionally agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/world/europe/uk-brexit-eu.html|title=U.K. Reaches Brexit Transition Deal With E.U.|last=Castle|first=Stephen|date=19 March 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=30 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629160826/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/world/europe/uk-brexit-eu.html|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] said that there had been little progress on the [[Brexit and the Irish border|Irish border question]]{{mdash}}on which the EU proposed a [[Irish backstop|backstop]], to come into effect if no overall trade deal had been reached by the end of the transition period{{mdash}}and that it was unlikely that there would be a solution before October, when the whole deal was to be agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/border-deal-is-not-likely-until-october-taoiseach-claims-1.3525988|title=Border deal is not likely until October, Taoiseach claims|date=11 June 2018|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=11 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711032020/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/border-deal-is-not-likely-until-october-taoiseach-claims-1.3525988|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, the UK government published the [[Chequers agreement|Chequers plan]], its aims for the future relationship to be determined in the negotiations. The plan sought to keep UK access to the single market for goods, but not necessarily for services, while allowing for an independent [[Commercial policy|trade policy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-explained-what-is-theresa-may-s-chequers-plan-1.3661485|title=Brexit explained: What is Theresa May's Chequers plan?|last=Carswell|first=Simon|date=12 October 2018|work=Irish Times|access-date=18 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815075412/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-explained-what-is-theresa-may-s-chequers-plan-1.3661485|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The plan caused cabinet resignations, including [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Brexit Secretary]] [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say|title=Brexit secretary David Davis resigns plunging government into crisis|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=9 July 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731123700/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Boris Johnson]].<ref name=\"S,C,S\">{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|last2=Crerar|first2=Pippa|last3=Sabbagh|first3=Dan|title=May's plan 'sticks in the throat', says Boris Johnson as he resigns over Brexit|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit|work=The Guardian|date=9 July 2018|access-date=31 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831034544/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit|archive-date=31 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Draft withdrawal agreement===\n{{Main|Brexit withdrawal agreement}}{{Wikisource|Draft Agreement on the Withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union|2018 Draft withdrawal agreement}}\nOn 13 November 2018, UK and EU negotiators agreed the text of a draft withdrawal agreement,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/uk-cabinet-meeting-wednesday-to-consider-brexit-technical-agreement/|title=Theresa May calls Cabinet meeting to approve Brexit 'draft agreement'|last=Cooper|first=Charlie|date=14 November 2018|work=Politico|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Bayer|first2=Lili|last3=Barigazzi|first3=Jacopo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185457/https://www.politico.eu/article/uk-cabinet-meeting-wednesday-to-consider-brexit-technical-agreement/|archive-date=30 December 2019}}</ref> and May secured her cabinet's backing of the deal the following day,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46215930|title=Brexit: Cabinet backs draft agreement|date=14 November 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419181835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46215930|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> though Brexit Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] resigned over \"fatal flaws\" in the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46219495|title=Brexit: Dominic Raab and Esther McVey among ministers to quit over EU agreement|date=15 November 2018|accessdate=15 November 2018|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617094908/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46219495|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was expected that ratification in the UK parliament would be difficult.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46334649|title=EU leaders agree UK's Brexit deal at Brussels summit|date=25 November 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910162614/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46334649|archive-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e1384dc86bcd418a9eeddd81fdb27f78|title=EU seals Brexit deal as May faces a hard sell at home|last=Cook|first=Lorne|date=25 November 2018|agency=Associated Press|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Lawless|first2=Jill|last3=Casert|first3=Raf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185501/https://apnews.com/e1384dc86bcd418a9eeddd81fdb27f78|archive-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/25/theresa-may-not-sad-but-defiant-makes-case-for-brexit-deal|title=Not sad but defiant: Theresa May makes case for Brexit deal|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=25 November 2018|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185458/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/25/theresa-may-not-sad-but-defiant-makes-case-for-brexit-deal|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref> On 25 November, all 27 leaders of the remaining EU countries endorsed the agreement.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Attempted ratification===\n{{main|Parliamentary votes on Brexit}}\n\nOn 10 December 2018, the Prime Minister postponed the vote in the House of Commons on her Brexit deal. The announcement came minutes after the [[Prime Minister's Office (United Kingdom)|Prime Minister's Office]] confirmed the vote would be going ahead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-delayed-postponed-theresa-may-commons-parliament-date-time-eu-deal-cabinet-a8675906.html|title=Theresa May calls off vote on Brexit deal after massive opposition from Tory rebels|date=10 December 2018|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619210106/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-delayed-postponed-theresa-may-commons-parliament-date-time-eu-deal-cabinet-a8675906.html|archive-date=19 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Faced with the prospect of a defeat in the House of Commons, this option gave May more time to negotiate with Conservative [[backbencher]]s and the EU, even though they had ruled out further discussions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/eu-figures-rule-out-concessions-as-theresa-may-postpones-brexit-vote|title=EU figures rule out concessions as May postpones Brexit vote|last=Boffey|first=Daniels|date=10 December 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522111207/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/eu-figures-rule-out-concessions-as-theresa-may-postpones-brexit-vote|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The decision was met with calls from many [[Welsh Labour]] MPs for a [[Motions of no confidence in the United Kingdom|motion of no confidence]] in the Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2018-12-11/welsh-labour-mps-call-for-no-confidence-vote/|title=Welsh Labour MPs call for no confidence vote|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708151738/https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2018-12-11/welsh-labour-mps-call-for-no-confidence-vote/|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Leader of the Opposition, [[Jeremy Corbyn]], described the government as being in \"disarray\".{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe [[European Research Group]] (ERG), a staunchly anti-EU grouping in Conservative Party, opposed the Prime Minister's proposed Withdrawal Agreement treaty. Its members objected strongly to the Withdrawal Agreement's inclusion of the [[Irish backstop]].<ref>Jessica Elgot & Heather Stewart, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/28/brexiter-mps-back-away-from-anti-backstop-brexit-amendment Theresa May splits Tories over anti-backstop Brexit deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226234115/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/28/brexiter-mps-back-away-from-anti-backstop-brexit-amendment |date=26 February 2019 }}, ''The Guardian'' (28 January 2019).</ref><ref>Laura Hughes, [https://www.ft.com/content/3e102106-ff00-11e8-ac00-57a2a826423e Eurosceptics still defiant over May's Brexit deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235625/https://www.ft.com/content/3e102106-ff00-11e8-ac00-57a2a826423e |date=26 February 2019 }}, ''Financial Times'' (13 December 2018).</ref> ERG members also objected to the proposed \u00a339 billion financial settlement with the EU and stated that the agreement would result in the UK's agreement to continuing to follow EU regulations in major policy areas; and to the continuing jurisdiction of the ECJ over interpretation of the agreement and of European law still applicable to the UK.<ref>William Booth, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/11/24/86b536a2-ef6b-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html May's plan for phasing Britain out of the E.U.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235549/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/11/24/86b536a2-ef6b-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html |date=26 February 2019 }}, ''Washington Post'' (25 November 2018).</ref><ref>Jack Maidment, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/11/18/eurosceptic-tories-publish-takedown-theresa-mays-brexit-deal/ Eurosceptic Tories publish analysis of Theresa May's Brexit deal and claim UK could pay EU \u00a339bn 'for nothing'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226234152/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/11/18/eurosceptic-tories-publish-takedown-theresa-mays-brexit-deal/ |date=26 February 2019 }}, ''The Daily Telegraph'' (18 November 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2019, the House of Commons voted 432 to 202 against the deal, which was the largest majority against a United Kingdom government ever.<ref name=\"Brexit: Theresa May's deal is voted down in historic Commons defeat\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46885828|title=Brexit: Theresa May's deal is voted down in historic Commons defeat|date=15 January 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430130037/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46885828|archive-date=30 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jan/15/how-did-your-mp-vote-on-mays-brexit-deal-meaningful-vote|title=How did your MP vote on May's Brexit deal?|last=Voce|first=Antonio|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 January 2019|last2=Clarke|first2=Se\u00e1n|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Voce|first3=Antonio|last4=Clarke|first4=Se\u00e1n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714042332/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jan/15/how-did-your-mp-vote-on-mays-brexit-deal-meaningful-vote|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after, [[2019 motion of no confidence in the May ministry|a motion of no confidence in Her Majesty's Government was tabled by the opposition]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/15/theresa-may-loses-brexit-deal-vote-by-majority-of-230|title=Theresa May loses Brexit deal vote by majority of 230|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=15 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 January 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713150628/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/15/theresa-may-loses-brexit-deal-vote-by-majority-of-230|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was rejected by 325 votes to 306.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/16/brexit-no-confidence-vote-result-theresa-may-news-latest/|title=No confidence vote result: Theresa May wins confidence vote but is snubbed by Jeremy Corbyn over cross-party Brexit talks|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=16 January 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=17 January 2019|last2=Maidment|first2=Jack|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|last3=Crisp|first3=James|last4=Yorke|first4=Harry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416171609/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/16/brexit-no-confidence-vote-result-theresa-may-news-latest/|archive-date=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, Prime Minister May announced that the next vote on the withdrawal agreement would be on 12 March 2019, 17 days away from Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another delay: Britain's May promises Brexit vote in parliament by March 12|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-may/another-delay-britains-may-promises-brexit-vote-in-parliament-by-march-12-idUSKCN1QD0J9|agency=Reuters|date=24 February 2019|access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524022507/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-may/another-delay-britains-may-promises-brexit-vote-in-parliament-by-march-12-idUSKCN1QD0J9|archive-date=24 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The deal was voted against 391 to 242, a loss of 149 votes down from 230 from when the deal was proposed in January.<ref name=\":24\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47547887|title=Brexit: MPs reject Theresa May's deal for a second time|date=13 March 2019|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313043330/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47547887|archive-date=13 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2019, the [[Speaker of the House of Commons|Speaker]] informed the House of Commons that a third meaningful vote could be held only on a [[Motion (parliamentary procedure)|motion]] that was significantly different from the previous one, citing parliamentary precedents going back to 1604.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47614074|title=Third Brexit vote must be different \u2013 Speaker|date=18 March 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318160131/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47614074|archive-date=18 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Withdrawal Agreement was brought back to the House without the attached understandings on 29 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47742395|title=Brexit: MPs face new vote on withdrawal deal|date=29 March 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329053108/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47742395|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Government's motion of support for the Withdrawal Agreement was lost by 344 votes to 286, a loss of 58 votes down from 149 from when the deal was proposed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47752017|title=Brexit: Brexit: MPs reject May's EU withdrawal agreement|date=29 March 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329145334/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47752017|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March and April extensions===\nOn 20 March 2019, the Prime Minister wrote to European Council President Tusk requesting that Brexit be postponed until 30 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47647515|title=Brexit: 'Tired' public needs a decision, says Theresa May|work=BBC News|date=20 March 2019|access-date=21 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321015120/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47647515|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March 2019, May presented her case to a European Council summit meeting in Brussels. After May left the meeting, a discussion amongst the remaining EU leaders resulted in the rejection of 30 June date and offered instead a choice of two new alternative Brexit dates. On 22 March 2019, the extension options were agreed between the UK government and the European Council.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a/> The first alternative offered was that if MPs rejected May's deal in the next week, Brexit would be due to occur by 12 April 2019, with, or without, a deal\u2014or alternatively another extension be asked for and a commitment to participate in the [[2019 European Parliament election]]s given. The second alternative offered was that if MPs approved May's deal, Brexit would be due to occur on 22 May 2019. The later date was the day before the start of European Parliament elections.<ref name=\"BBC_20190322\">{{cite news|date=22 March 2019|title=Brexit: Theresa May to urge MPs to back deal as delay agreed|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47663031|work=BBC News|access-date=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322051804/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47663031|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the government deemed unwarranted the concerns over the legality of the proposed change (because it contained two possible exit dates) the previous day,<ref name=Express2019-03-26a>{{cite news|title=Get us out NOW! May's Brexit delay 'UNLAWFUL' \u2013 MPs issue shock legal block|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/1105321/Brexit-latest-news-theresa-may-indicative-votes-commons-latest|date=26 March 2019|accessdate=28 March 2019|author=Ciaran McGrath|work=Daily Express|quote=...{{nbsp}}Brexiteer MPs led by Sir Bill Cash have written to Mrs May warning of their \"serious legal objections\" to her decision to delay Article 50, and hence Brexit, beyond 29 March.{{nbsp}}... The Government is confident a proposed law change altering the Brexit date is \"legally correct\" in response to concerns raised by lawyers. Ministers were pressed over the legality of the statutory instrument (SI) to change the exit day of the UK's withdrawal from the EU by Lord Pannick, who successfully led the Supreme Court Article 50 case against the Government.{{nbsp}}... The concern centres on the SI, due to be debated by peers and MPs on Wednesday, containing two alternative exit days.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327191711/https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/1105321/Brexit-latest-news-theresa-may-indicative-votes-commons-latest|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=TWFY2019-03-26a>{{cite web|title=Amendment to the Motion \u2013 Business of the House \u2013 Motion to Agree \u2013 in the House of Lords at 3:06 pm on 26th&nbsp;March 2019.|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-03-26b.1715.1|date=26 March 2019|accessdate=28 March 2019|publisher=[[TheyWorkForYou]]|quote=...{{nbsp}}Lord Pannick:{{nbsp}}... A number of lawyers have expressed concern about the legality of this statutory instrument. The concern is that it sets out two alternative exit days: 12 April or 22 May.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328104029/https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-03-26b.1715.1|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> on 27 March 2019 both the Lords (without a vote)<ref name=Guardian2019-03-27a>{{cite web|title=All eight indicative vote options on Brexit defeated by MPs \u2013 as it happened|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/mar/27/brexit-latest-news-live-debate-indicative-votes--to-vote-on-alternative-votes-as-speculation-mounts-may-could-announce-plans-to-quit-live-news?page=with:block-5c9bdf12e4b08334583633d3|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=28 March 2019|author1=Andrew Sparrow|authorlink1=Andrew Sparrow|author2=Jedidajah Otte|work=The Guardian|quote=The statutory instrument needs to be passed by both the Commons and the Lords. In the Lords peers passed it earlier today, without a division|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328080933/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/mar/27/brexit-latest-news-live-debate-indicative-votes--to-vote-on-alternative-votes-as-speculation-mounts-may-could-announce-plans-to-quit-live-news?page=with:block-5c9bdf12e4b08334583633d3|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the Commons (by 441 to 105) approved the statutory instrument changing the exit date to 22 May 2019 if a withdrawal deal is approved, or 12 April 2019 if it is not.<ref name=FT2019-03-27a>{{cite news|title=MPs vote down rival Brexit plans as May offers to resign \u2013 as it happened|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ec9ee89c-a1a7-3c88-a8c3-3818f3781d4f|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=28 March 2019|author=Daniel Thomas|work=Financial Times|quote=MPs delay Brexit date by 441 to 105|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328074207/https://www.ft.com/content/ec9ee89c-a1a7-3c88-a8c3-3818f3781d4f|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The amendment was then signed into law at 12:40&nbsp;p.m. the next day.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a/>\n\nFollowing the failure of the UK Parliament to approve the Withdrawal Agreement by 29 March, the UK was required to leave the EU on 12 April 2019. On 10 April 2019, late-night talks in Brussels resulted in a further extension, to 31 October 2019; Theresa May had again requested an extension only until 30 June. Under the terms of this new extension, if the Withdrawal Agreement were to be passed before October, Brexit would occur on the first day of the subsequent month. The UK would then be obligated to hold European Parliament elections in May, or leave the EU on 1 June without a deal. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47889404|title=New Brexit deadline set for 31&nbsp;October|date=11 April 2019|access-date=11 April 2019|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411015652/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47889404|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/39042/10-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf|title=Special meeting of the European Council (Art. 50) (10&nbsp;April 2019) \u2013 Conclusions|last=European Council|date=10 April 2019|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411085340/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/39042/10-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Revised withdrawal agreement===\nIn granting the Article 50 extensions, the EU adopted a stance of refusing to \"reopen\" (that is, renegotiate) the Withdrawal Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2019/03/21/european-council-art-50-conclusions-21-march-2019/|title=European Council Art. 50 conclusions, 21 March 2019|last=|first=|date=21 March 2019|website=|publisher=European Council|access-date=20 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023020612/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2019/03/21/european-council-art-50-conclusions-21-march-2019/|archive-date=23 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Boris Johnson became prime minister on 24 July 2019 and met with EU leaders, the EU changed its stance. On 17 October 2019, following \"tunnel talks\" between UK and EU,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/11/entering-the-tunnel-what-does-it-mean-for-brexit-talks|title=Entering 'the tunnel': what does it mean for the Brexit talks?|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=11 October 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017024529/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/11/entering-the-tunnel-what-does-it-mean-for-brexit-talks|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> a revised withdrawal agreement was agreed on negotiators level, and endorsed by the UK government and the EU Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/c2019_8000_7_en_act.pdf|title=European Commission Recommendation|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|website=|publisher=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017132754/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/c2019_8000_7_en_act.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> The revised deal contained a new [[Northern Ireland Protocol]], as well as technical modifications to related articles.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> In addition, the Political Declaration was also revised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_political_declaration.pdf|title=Revised Political Declaration|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|website=|publisher=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017135747/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_political_declaration.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> The revised deal and the political declaration was endorsed by the [[European Council]] later that day.<ref>{{cite web|title=The UK and EU have a new Brexit agreement. But it's not a done deal yet.|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2019/10/17/20918879/brexit-deal-boris-johnson-european-union-irish-backstop|last=Kirby|first=Jen|publisher=Vox|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102022613/https://www.vox.com/world/2019/10/17/20918879/brexit-deal-boris-johnson-european-union-irish-backstop|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To come into effect, it needs to be ratified by the [[European Parliament]] and the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK parliament]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-and-uk-say-they-have-brexit-deal/|title=EU and UK say they have Brexit deal|last=Herszenhorn|first=David M.|date=17 October 2019|work=Politico|access-date=17 October 2019|last2=Casalicchio|first2=Emilio|last3=Courea|first3=Eleni|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017113546/https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-and-uk-say-they-have-brexit-deal/|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===October 2019 extension===\nThe UK Parliament passed the [[European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019]], which received [[Royal Assent]] on 9 September 2019, obliging the Prime Minister to seek a third extension if no agreement has been reached at the next European Council meeting in October 2019.<ref>{{cite act|date=9 September 2019|title=European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/26|accessdate=14 October 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929042010/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/26|archivedate=29 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In order for such an extension to be granted if it is requested by the Prime Minister, it would be necessary for there to be unanimous agreement by all other heads of EU governments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49612757|title=Can a no-deal Brexit still happen?|last=Kraemer|first=Daniel|date=27 September 2019|access-date=1 October 2019|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001051353/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49612757|archive-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 October 2019, the third extension was agreed to by the EU, with a new withdrawal deadline of 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603|title=Brexit: European leaders agree extension to 31 January|date=28 October 2019|access-date=28 October 2019|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028093707/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603|archive-date=28 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> 'Exit day' in UK law was then amended to this new date by statutory instrument on 30 October 2019.<ref name=SI2019-10-30a/>\n\n===Ratification and departure===\nIn October, the UK parliament passed the [[Early Parliamentary General Election Act 2019|Early Parliamentary General Election Act]] that bypassed the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011|Fixed-term Parliament Act 2011]] and called a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] for 12 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/29/enacted/data.htm|title=Early Parliamentary General Election Act 2019|last=|first=|date=31 October 2019|work=legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the election, Boris Johnson's campaign was focused on \"[[Get Brexit Done|get Brexit done]]\", and the Conservative Party won an 80-seat majority in parliament. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50765773|title=Election results 2019: Boris Johnson returns to power with big majority|last=Staff|date=13 December 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218184111/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50765773|archive-date=18 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, the government introduced a bill to ratify the withdrawal agreement. It passed its second reading in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in a 358\u2013234 vote on 20 December,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/20/brexit-pm-asks-britons-to-move-on-as-mps-debate-withdrawal-bill|title=Brexit: parliament passes withdrawal agreement bill by 124 majority|last=editor|first=Heather Stewart Political|date=20 December 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=20 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220113442/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/20/brexit-pm-asks-britons-to-move-on-as-mps-debate-withdrawal-bill|archive-date=20 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and became law on 23 January\nas the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-51221727/brexit-bill-receives-royal-assent|title=Brexit bill receives Royal Assent|last=|first=|date=23 January 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201235201/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-51221727/brexit-bill-receives-royal-assent|archive-date=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe withdrawal agreement received the backing of the [[European Parliament Committee on Constitutional Affairs|constitutional committee]] in the [[European Parliament]] on 23 January, setting expectation that the entire parliament would approved it in a later vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-23/brexit-deal-passes-penultimate-eu-hurdle-with-committee-approval|title=Brexit Deal Passes Penultimate EU Hurdle With Committee Approval|last=Wishart|first=Ian|date=23 January 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126193820/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-23/brexit-deal-passes-penultimate-eu-hurdle-with-committee-approval|archive-date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51244126|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street|date=24 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125041950/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51244126|archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/world/europe/brexit-withdrawal-bill.html/|title=U.K. Takes a Major Step Toward Brexit|last=Castle|first=Stephen|date=22 January 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126044640/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/world/europe/brexit-withdrawal-bill.html|archive-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> On the following day, [[Ursula von der Leyen]] and [[Charles Michel]] signed the withdrawal agreement in Brussels, and it was sent to London where Boris Johnson signed it.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement|title=Boris Johnson signs Brexit withdrawal agreement|last1=Boffey|first1=Daniel|last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|date=24 January 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124122448/https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement|archive-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The European Parliament gave its consent to ratification on 29 January by the votes 621 to 49.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/european-parliament-ratifies-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-ahead-of-exit-day-11921016|title=European Parliament ratifies Boris Johnson's Brexit deal ahead of exit day|last=McGuinness|first=Alan|date=29 January 2020|work=Sky News|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195015/https://news.sky.com/story/european-parliament-ratifies-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-ahead-of-exit-day-11921016|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"sparrow1\"/> Immediately after voting approval, members of the European Parliament joined hands and sang ''[[Auld Lang Syne]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/video-european-parliament-sings-auld-lang-syne-after-approving-brexit-2020-1|title=The European Parliament joined hands and sang Auld Lang Syne in an emotional Brexit farewell to the UK|last=Payne|first=Adam|date=January 30, 2020|work=Reuters|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154336/https://www.businessinsider.com/video-european-parliament-sings-auld-lang-syne-after-approving-brexit-2020-1|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Council of the European Union]] concluded EU ratification the following day.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/europe/eu-brexit-decision.html Press send for Brexit: EU seals UK withdrawal by email] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154556/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/europe/eu-brexit-decision.html |date=31 January 2020 }}, The New York Times, 30 January 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 31 January at 11 p.m. [[GMT]], the United Kingdom's membership of the [[European Union]] ended 47 years after it joined.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>{{update after|2020|2|8}}<!-- and then what? this article really needs a section on \"what is actually happening\" now that UK has withdrawn.  And the details on the long process of withdrawl from 2016 to Jan 2020 can be relegated to an article section that describes the process leading up to the event.  But that process is not Brexit.  It is just a part of Brexit -->\n\n==Political developments within UK==\n===Domestic legislation after Article 50 notification===\n\n====European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018====\n{{Main|European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018}}\n\nIn October 2016, Theresa May promised a \"Great Repeal Bill\", which would repeal the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|European Communities Act 1972]] and restate in UK law all enactments previously in force under EU law. Subsequently renamed the European Union (Withdrawal) bill, it was introduced to the House of Commons on 13 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/europeanunionwithdrawal.html|title=European Union (Withdrawal) Bill 2017\u201319 \u2013 UK Parliament|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|access-date=23 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725141501/https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/europeanunionwithdrawal.html|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2017, the bill passed its first vote and second reading by a margin of 326 votes to 290 votes in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41235522|title=EU repeal bill wins first Commons vote|date=12 September 2017|access-date=1 November 2017|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155411/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41235522|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill was further amended on a series of votes in both Houses. After the Act became law on 26 June 2018, the European Council decided on 29 June to renew its call on Member States and Union institutions to step up their work on preparedness at all levels and for all outcomes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35966/29-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf|title=Conclusions adopted by the European Council (Art. 50), 29&nbsp;June 2018|website=europa.eu|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214172737/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35966/29-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf|archive-date=14 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Withdrawal Act fixed the period ending 21 January 2019 for the government to decide on how to proceed if the negotiations have not reached agreement in principle on both the withdrawal arrangements and the framework for the future relationship between the UK and EU; while, alternatively, making future ratification of the withdrawal agreement as a treaty between the UK and EU depend upon the prior enactment of another act of Parliament for approving the final terms of withdrawal when the current [[Brexit negotiations]] are completed. In any event, the act does not alter the two-year period for negotiating allowed by Article 50 that ends at the latest on 29 March 2019 if the UK has not by then ratified a withdrawal agreement or agreed a prolongation of the negotiating period.<ref name=ExitDay01a/>\n\nThe Withdrawal Act which became law in June 2018 allows for various outcomes including no negotiated settlement. It authorises the government to bring into force, by [[Statutory instrument (UK)|order]] made under section 25, the provisions that fix \"exit day\" and the repeal of the European Communities Act 1972, but exit day must be the same day and time as when the EU Treaties are to cease to apply to the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/brexit/negotiations/what-is-exit-day-dispelling-misconceptions-about-the-extension-of-article-50/|title=What is \"exit day\"? Dispelling misconceptions about the extension of Article 50|publisher=House of Commons Library|date=19 March 2019|access-date=21 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321190114/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/brexit/negotiations/what-is-exit-day-dispelling-misconceptions-about-the-extension-of-article-50/|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Exit day====\nExit day was 31 January 2020 at 11.00 p.m. [[GMT]]<ref name=SI2019-10-30a>The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 3) Regulations 2019 SI 2019 No. 1423, 30 October 2019.[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/regulation/2/made] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110011230/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/regulation/2/made |date=10 November 2019 }}([http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/made more detailed version] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115183425/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/made |date=15 November 2019 }})</ref> The [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]] (as amended by a UK [[Statutory Instrument]] on 11 April 2019), in section 20 (1), defined 'exit day' as 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on 31 October 2019.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a>{{cite web|title=Statutory Instruments \u2013 2019 No. 859 \u2013 Exiting The European Union \u2013 The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 2) Regulations 2019|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/859/pdfs/uksi_20190859_en.pdf|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=13 April 2019|publisher=[[The Stationery Office Limited]]|quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417225120/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/859/pdfs/uksi_20190859_en.pdf|archive-date=17 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Originally, 'exit day' was defined as 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on 29 March 2019 GMT ([[UTC+0]]).<ref name=ExitDay01a>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/contents/enacted/data.htm|publisher=legislation.gov.uk|title=European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018<!-- Ch. 16 -->|accessdate=13 February 2019|date=2018|quote=\"exit day\" means 29 March 2019 at 11.00 p.m.(and see subsections (2) to (5));|at=sec.&nbsp;20(1)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206234328/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/contents/enacted/data.htm|archive-date=6 February 2019|url-status=live}} Subsections (2) to (5) provide the option of amending the date by a Ministerial Regulation \"if the day or time on or at which the Treaties are to cease to apply to the United Kingdom in accordance with Article 50(3) of the Treaty on European Union is different from that specified in the definition of 'exit day' in subsection (1).\" Article 50(3) of the [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:12012M/TXT Treaty on European Union] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231181056/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A12012M%2FTXT |date=31 December 2019 }} states: The Treaties shall cease to apply to the State in question from the date of entry into force of the withdrawal agreement or, failing that, two years after the notification referred to in paragraph 2, unless the European Council, in agreement with the Member State concerned, unanimously decides to extend this period.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The UK legislation states the day and hour as \"29 March 2019 at 11.00 p.m.\" in the knowledge that the UK [[Interpretation Act 1978]] s.4 (a) prescribes that \"An Act or provision of an Act comes into force where provision is made for it to come into force on a particular day, at the beginning of that day\".}}<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-timeline/key-dates-in-brexit-process-idUSKBN1FM2H9|title=Key dates in Brexit process|date=2 February 2018|work=Reuters|accessdate=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924163923/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-timeline/key-dates-in-brexit-process-idUSKBN1FM2H9|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7960|title=House of Commons Briefing Paper 7960, summary|website=House of Commons|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=16 February 2019|last1=Walker|first1=Nigel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216153321/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7960|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.consilium.europa.eu/doc/document/XT-21016-2017-ADD-1-REV-2/en/pdf|title=''Directives for the negotiation of an agreement with the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland setting out the arrangements for its withdrawal from the European Union'' (Section II.8)|publisher=Europa (web portal)|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118063517/http://data.consilium.europa.eu/doc/document/XT-21016-2017-ADD-1-REV-2/en/pdf|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Additional government bills====\nA report published in March 2017 by the [[Institute for Government]] commented that, in addition to the European Union (Withdrawal) bill, primary and secondary legislation will be needed to cover the gaps in policy areas such as customs, immigration and agriculture.<ref>Hannah White and Jill Rutter, \"Legislating Brexit: The Great Repeal Bill and the wider legislative challenge\", Institute for Government, 20 March 2017, p.{{nbsp}}9 [https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/IFGJ5347-Legislating-Brexit-IFG-Analysis-032017-WEB.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321154433/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/IFGJ5347-Legislating-Brexit-IFG-Analysis-032017-WEB.pdf |date=21 March 2017 }}</ref> The report also commented that the role of the devolved legislatures was unclear, and could cause problems, and as many as 15 new additional Brexit Bills may be required, which would involve strict prioritisation and limiting Parliamentary time for in-depth examination of new legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39322297|title=Brexit could place 'huge burden' on Parliament|publisher=BBC|date=20 March 2017|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727015516/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39322297|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 and 2017, the House of Lords published a series of reports on Brexit-related subjects, including:\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-3}}\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/72/72.pdf Brexit: the options for trade]\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/76/76.pdf Brexit: UK-Irish relations]\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/77/77.pdf Brexit: future UK-EU security and police cooperation]\n{{col-3}}\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/78/78.pdf Brexit: fisheries]\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/109/109.pdf Brexit: environment and climate change]\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/136/136.pdf Brexit: the Crown Dependencies]\n{{col-3}}\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/134/134.pdf Brexit: justice for families, individuals and businesses?]\n* [https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/135/135.pdf Brexit: trade in non-financial services]\n{{col-end}}\n\n=====Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018=====\nThe [[Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018]], relating to withdrawal from Euratom, was presented to Parliament in October 2017. The act makes provision about nuclear safeguards, and for connected\npurposes. The Secretary of State may by regulations (\"nuclear safeguards regulations\") make provision for the purpose of \u2014 (a) ensuring that qualifying nuclear material, facilities or\nequipment are available only for use for civil activities (whether in the UK or elsewhere), or (b) giving effect to provisions of a relevant international agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/15/pdfs/ukpga_20180015_en.pdf|title=Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=3 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214033335/https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/15/pdfs/ukpga_20180015_en.pdf|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2017 British general election===\nA [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]] was held on 8 June 2017, announced at short notice by the new Prime Minister May. The Conservative Party, Labour and UKIP made manifesto pledges to implement the referendum, the Labour manifesto differing in its approach to Brexit negotiations, such as unilaterally offering permanent residence to EU immigrants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|title=Theresa May calls for general election to secure Brexit mandate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/18/theresa-may-calls-for-general-election-in-bid-to-secure-brexit-mandate|accessdate=19 April 2017|work=The Guardian|date=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712181222/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/18/theresa-may-calls-for-general-election-in-bid-to-secure-brexit-mandate|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39742407|title=General election 2017: UKIP needed to stop Brexit 'backsliding'|date=28 April 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=29 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727070503/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39742407|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/24/labour-vows-to-rip-up-and-rethink-brexit-white-paper|title=Labour vows to rip up and rethink Brexit white paper|author=Anushka Asthana|date=24 April 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714160342/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/24/labour-vows-to-rip-up-and-rethink-brexit-white-paper|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39698465|title=General Election 2017: Labour's 'day one' pledge to EU nationals|date=25 April 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727061457/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39698465|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Liberal Democrat Party and the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] manifestos proposed a policy of remaining in the EU via a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|title='This is your chance,' Lib Dems tell voters opposed to Hard Brexit|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15230750._This_is_your_chance___Lib_Dems_tell_voters_opposed_to_Hard_Brexit/|accessdate=23 April 2017|work=The Herald|date=18 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825114208/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15230750._This_is_your_chance___Lib_Dems_tell_voters_opposed_to_Hard_Brexit/|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-second-eu-referendum-green-party-caroline-lucas-leader-elected-a7222221.html|title=Green Party leader Caroline Lucas calls for second EU referendum|date=2 September 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=19 April 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612060902/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-second-eu-referendum-green-party-caroline-lucas-leader-elected-a7222221.html|archive-date=12 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tim-farron-general-election-liberal-democrat-leader-snap-change-country-direction-chance-june-8-a7688486.html|title=Lib Dem leader Tim Farron responds to Theresa May's general election announcement|date=18 April 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=19 April 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705211044/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tim-farron-general-election-liberal-democrat-leader-snap-change-country-direction-chance-june-8-a7688486.html|archive-date=5 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Scottish National Party (SNP) manifesto proposed a policy of waiting for the outcome of the Brexit negotiations and then holding a referendum on [[Scottish independence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/9544/attachments/original/1496320559/Manifesto_06_01_17.pdf?1496320559|title=Stronger for Scotland|first=|last=|date=1 June 2017|access-date=13 June 2018|publisher=SNP website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609083758/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/9544/attachments/original/1496320559/Manifesto_06_01_17.pdf?1496320559|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40091999|title=SNP manifesto summary: Key points at-a-glance|work=BBC News|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=13 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206031824/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40091999|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Compared to the 2015 general election, the Conservatives gained votes (but nevertheless lost seats and their majority in the House of Commons). Labour gained significantly on votes and seats, retaining its position as the second-largest party. The [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] also made gains in votes and seats. Parties losing votes included the SNP, Liberal Democrats, Greens, and especially UKIP.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2017/results|title=Election 2017 Results|work=BBC News|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=13 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531172514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2017/results|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2017, Conservatives and the DUP reached a [[confidence and supply]] agreement whereby the DUP would back the Conservatives in key votes in the House of Commons over the course of the parliament. The agreement included additional funding of \u00a31&nbsp;billion for Northern Ireland, highlighted mutual support for Brexit and national security, expressed commitment to the Good Friday Agreement, and indicated that policies such as the state pension triple lock and [[Winter Fuel Payment]]s would be maintained.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40403434|title=Conservatives agree pact with DUP to support May government|date=26 June 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728173408/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40403434|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Public opinion===\n{{further|Opinion polling on the United Kingdom's membership of the European Union (2016\u2013present)}}\n{{Update|section|date=March 2020|updated=October 2019}}\n[[File:Westminster_(49470120328).jpg|thumb|31 January 2020]]\n\nOpinion polling overall showed an initial fall in support for Brexit from the referendum to late 2016, when responses were split evenly between support and opposition. Support rose again to a plurality until the 2017 General Election. Since then, opinion polls tended to show a plurality of support for remaining in the EU or for the view that Brexit was a mistake, with the estimated margin increasing until a small decrease in 2019 (to 53% Remain : 47% Leave, {{as of|2019|10|lc=1}}).<ref name=OctoberPollOfPolls>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-news-latest-britain-against-leaving-eu-as-poll-of-polls-says-most-now-want-to-stay-a4257476.html|title=Brexit news latest: Poll of polls says Britain is now against leaving EU as most want to stay|last=Cecil|first=Nicholas|date=10 October 2019|website=Evening Standard|publisher=London Evening Standard|access-date=19 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016201243/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-news-latest-britain-against-leaving-eu-as-poll-of-polls-says-most-now-want-to-stay-a4257476.html|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This seems to be largely due to a preference for remaining in the EU among those who did not vote in 2016's referendum (an estimated 2.5 million of whom, {{As of|2019|October|lc=1}}, were [[Voting age#United Kingdom|too young to vote]] at the time).<ref name=IndependentDemographics>{{cite news|last=Kellner|first=Peter|date=10 October 2019|title=Everyone says they know what the public think about Brexit \u2013 here's the polling data that tells you who's right|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/brexit-myths-busting-polling-second-referendum-leave-remain-a9149491.html|work=The Independent|access-date=16 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016201237/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/brexit-myths-busting-polling-second-referendum-leave-remain-a9149491.html|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatukthinks.org/eu/has-there-been-a-shift-in-support-for-brexit/|title=Has There Been a Shift in Support for Brexit?|last=Curtice|first=John|date=8 February 2019|website=What UK Thinks|publisher=|access-date=16 May 2019|quote=Until the 2017 general election typically more people said that the decision to leave the EU was right than stated it was wrong. Since then the oppose has been the case{{nbsp}}... The reason why the balance of opinion had shifted in favour of Remain, even though very few Leave voters had changed their minds, was because those who had not voted before (in some cases because they had been too young to do so) were now decisively in favour of Remain.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516224825/https://whatukthinks.org/eu/has-there-been-a-shift-in-support-for-brexit/|archive-date=16 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Other reasons suggested include slightly more Leave voters than Remain voters (14% and 12% of each, respectively, {{as of|2019|10|lc=1}})<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50043549 |title=Have UK voters changed their minds on Brexit? |last=Curtice |first=John |date=17 October 2019 |work=BBC News |access-date=23 October 2019 |quote=On average, during the last month, polls that ask people how they would vote in another referendum suggest that 88% of those who backed Remain would do so again. Among those who voted Leave, 86% have not changed their minds. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023163831/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50043549 |archive-date=23 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> changing how they would vote (particularly in [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] areas) and the deaths of older voters,<ref name=OctoberPollOfPolls /> most of whom voted to leave the EU. One estimate of demographic changes (ignoring other effects) implies that had an EU referendum taken place {{As of|alt=in October 2019|2019|10|post=,}} there would have been between 800,000 and 900,000 fewer Leave voters and between 600,000 and 700,000 more Remain voters, resulting in a Remain majority.<ref name=IndependentDemographics />\n\nIn March 2019, a [[Revoke Article 50 and remain in the EU petition|petition]] submitted to the UK Parliament petitions website, calling on the government to revoke Article 50 and stay in the EU, reached a record-level of more than 6.1 million signatures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/31/article-50-petition-to-cancel-brexit-passes-6m-signatures|title=Article 50 petition to cancel Brexit passes 6m signatures|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403074151/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/31/article-50-petition-to-cancel-brexit-passes-6m-signatures|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47772682|title=Article 50: MPs debate six-million-signature petition|work=BBC News|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410101020/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47772682|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\" caption=\"Post-referendum opinion polling\">\nFile:Brexit post-referendum polling - Right-Wrong.svg|Opinion polling on whether the UK was right or wrong to vote to leave the EU\nFile:Brexit post-referendum polling - Remain-Leave-Neither.svg|Opinion polling on whether the UK should leave or remain in the EU, including \"Neither\" responses\nFile:Brexit post-referendum polling - Remain-Leave.svg|Opinion polling on whether the UK should leave or remain in the EU, excluding \"Neither\" responses and normalised\n</gallery>\n\n===Scotland===\n[[File:Nicola Sturgeon addresses journalists over Brexit.jpg|thumb|right|[[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] with journalists at [[Bute House]]]]\n\nAfter the Brexit referendum, the [[Scottish Government]]\u2014led by the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP)\u2014announced that officials were planning [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|another independence referendum]] because Scotland voted to remain in the EU while England and Wales voted to leave.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/world/europe/brexit-scotland-independence-referendum.html|title=Scotland Says New Vote on Independence Is 'Highly Likely'|date=25 June 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=17 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216050257/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/world/europe/brexit-scotland-independence-referendum.html|archive-date=16 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It had suggested this before the Brexit referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/24/nicola-sturgeon-denies-she-has-machiavellian-wish-for-brexit_n_9063372.html|title=Nicola Sturgeon Denies She Has \"Machiavellian\" Wish For Brexit|last=Simons|first=Ned|date=24 January 2016|website=The Huffington Post UK|accessdate=3 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203234636/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/24/nicola-sturgeon-denies-she-has-machiavellian-wish-for-brexit_n_9063372.html|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[First Minister of Scotland]], [[Nicola Sturgeon]], requested a referendum be held before the UK's withdrawal, but the UK Prime Minister rejected this timing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=16 March 2017|title=Theresa May rejects Nicola Sturgeon's referendum demand|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/16/theresa-may-rejects-nicola-sturgeons-scottish-referendum-demand|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531114753/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/16/theresa-may-rejects-nicola-sturgeons-scottish-referendum-demand|archive-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Scottish Parliament voted in favour of holding another independence referendum, with Sturgeon planning it for 2021.<ref name=\"MassDemo-Tagesschau.de-06102019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/schotten-103.html|title=Schottland \u2013 Massendemo f\u00fcr die Unabh\u00e4ngigkeit|trans-title=Scotland \u2013 mass demonstration for independence|date=6 October 2019|publisher=[[Tagesschau (German TV series)|tagesschau.de]]|language=German|accessdate=8 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006183345/https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/schotten-103.html|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Brexit-Spiegel-Online-06102019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/brexit-verhandlungen-will-boris-johnson-verlaengerung-per-veto-torpedieren-a-1290201.html#ref=rss|title=Brexit-Verhandlungen \u2013 Tittle-Tattle|trans-title=Brexit Negotiations \u2013 Tittle-Tattle|author=ala/[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur|dpa]]/[[Reuters]]/[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]|date=6 October 2019|work=[[Spiegel Online]]|language=German|accessdate=8 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007143652/https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/brexit-verhandlungen-will-boris-johnson-verlaengerung-per-veto-torpedieren-a-1290201.html#ref=rss|archive-date=7 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the last referendum in 2014, 55% of voters had decided to remain in the UK, but the referendum on Britain's withdrawal from the EU was held in 2016, with 62% of Scottish voters against it. In the event that Northern Ireland remains associated with the EU \u2013 for example, by remaining in the Customs Union \u2013 it is expected that Scotland will also insist on special treatment.<ref name=\"Brexit-Reuters-04122017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-deals/scotland-wales-and-london-want-special-brexit-deal-if-northern-ireland-gets-one-idUSKBN1DY24L|title=Scotland, Wales and London want special Brexit deal if Northern Ireland gets one|date=4 December 2017|work=Reuters|language=English|accessdate=8 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008152318/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-deals/scotland-wales-and-london-want-special-brexit-deal-if-northern-ireland-gets-one-idUSKBN1DY24L|archive-date=8 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2018, the Scottish Parliament passed the [[UK Withdrawal from the European Union (Legal Continuity) (Scotland) Bill|Scottish Continuity Bill]].<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16110743.Whitehall_lawyers_drawing_up_plans_to_challenge_Continuity_Bill_in_courts/|title=Whitehall lawyers drawing up plans to challenge Continuity Bill in courts|work=Herald Scotland|date=2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403175132/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16110743.Whitehall_lawyers_drawing_up_plans_to_challenge_Continuity_Bill_in_courts/|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This was passed by stalling negotiations between the Scottish Government and the British Government on where powers within devolved policy areas should lie after Brexit. The Act allows for all devolved policy areas to remain within the remit of the Scottish Parliament and reduces the executive power upon exit day that the UK Withdrawal Bill provides for Ministers of the Crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/businessreview/2018/03/17/forging-a-new-uk-wide-agricultural-framework-post-brexit/|title=Forging a new UK-wide agricultural framework post-Brexit|publisher=LSE|date=2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403173752/http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/businessreview/2018/03/17/forging-a-new-uk-wide-agricultural-framework-post-brexit/|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill was referred to the UK Supreme Court, which found that it could not come into force as the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]], which received royal assent between the Scottish Parliament passing its bill and the Supreme Court's judgement, designated itself under Schedule{{nbsp}}4 of the [[Scotland Act 1998]] as unamendable by the Scottish Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/schedule/3/paragraph/21/enacted/data.htm|title=European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806182954/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/schedule/3/paragraph/21/enacted/data.htm|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill has therefore not received royal assent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/eu-continuity-bill-was-within-competence-scottish-parliament-when-it-was-passed|title=EU Continuity Bill was within competence of Scottish Parliament when it was passed|date=13 December 2018|website=Holyrood Magazine|language=en|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806112407/https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/eu-continuity-bill-was-within-competence-scottish-parliament-when-it-was-passed|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===No-deal planning===\n{{See also|No-deal Brexit|Operation Yellowhammer}}\n\nOn 19 December 2018, the EU Commission announced its \"no-deal\" Contingency Action Plan in specific sectors, in respect of the UK leaving the EU \"in 100 days' time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-6851_en.htm|title=European Commission \u2013 PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Brexit: European Commission implements \"no-deal\" Contingency Action Plan in specific sectors|website=europa.eu|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905165240/https://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-6851_en.htm|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the United Kingdom's vote to leave the European Union, the [[Department for International Trade]] (DIT) for reaching and extending trade agreements between the UK and non-EU states was created by Prime Minister May, shortly after she took office on 13 July 2016.<ref name=\"csw new article\">{{cite web|url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/theresa-may-signals-whitehall-rejig-two-new-cabinet-posts|title=Theresa May signals Whitehall rejig with two new Cabinet posts|website=civilserviceworld.com|publisher=CSW|accessdate=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714151146/http://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/theresa-may-signals-whitehall-rejig-two-new-cabinet-posts|archive-date=14 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2017, it employed about 200 trade negotiators<ref name=\"economist2017\">Trading places / Negotiating post-Brexit deals. Economist, 4\u201310 February 2017, p. 25</ref> and was overseen by then [[Secretary of State for International Trade]] [[Liam Fox]]. In March 2019, the UK government announced that it would cut many import tariffs to zero, in the event of a no-deal Brexit.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/temporary-tariff-regime-for-no-deal-brexit-published|title=Temporary tariff regime for no deal Brexit published|website=GOV.UK|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183755/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/temporary-tariff-regime-for-no-deal-brexit-published|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Confederation of British Industry]] said the move would be a \"sledgehammer for our economy\",<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/13/brexit-tariffs-on-87-of-uk-imports-cut-to-zero-in-temporary-no-deal-plan|title=UK will cut most tariffs to zero in event of no-deal Brexit|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Lisa|last2=Boffey|first2=Daniel|date=13 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314110111/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/13/brexit-tariffs-on-87-of-uk-imports-cut-to-zero-in-temporary-no-deal-plan|archive-date=14 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/car-prices-rise-1500-no-15965400|title=Car prices to rise by \u00a31,500 as no-deal tariffs are revealed|last1=Glaze|first1=Ben|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|date=13 March 2019|website=walesonline|last3=Owen|first3=Cathy|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172608/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/car-prices-rise-1500-no-15965400|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aol.co.uk/news/2019/03/13/no-deal-tariff-regime-would-be-a-sledgehammera-to-uk-economy/|title=No-deal tariff regime would be 'sledgehammer' to UK economy, CBI warns|website=Aol.co.uk|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172648/https://www.aol.co.uk/news/2019/03/13/no-deal-tariff-regime-would-be-a-sledgehammera-to-uk-economy/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[National Farmers' Union of England and Wales|National Farmer's Union]] was also highly critical.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-explained/brexit-no-deal-farmers-eu-tariffs-food-costs-imports-theresa-may-a8821096.html|title=This is why farmers are suddenly very worried about a no-deal Brexit|date=13 March 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329185311/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-explained/brexit-no-deal-farmers-eu-tariffs-food-costs-imports-theresa-may-a8821096.html|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, the plan appeared to breach standard WTO rules.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47551121|title=No-deal plans a bid 'to break EU unity'|date=13 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331063145/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47551121|archive-date=31 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\" /><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/03/13/uk-s-zero-tariff-plan-for-no-deal-brexit-would-not-spare-some-eu-imports|title=UK zero-tariff plan for no-deal Brexit would not spare some EU imports|last=Sandford|first=Alisdair|date=13 March 2019|website=Euronews.com|format=PDF|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172729/https://www.euronews.com/2019/03/13/uk-s-zero-tariff-plan-for-no-deal-brexit-would-not-spare-some-eu-imports|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47559880|title=Does NI tariffs plan violate WTO law?|last=McCormack|first=Jayne|date=14 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403154914/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47559880|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-tariffs-idUKKBN1QU1J9|title=EU to apply normal tariffs on trade with UK in case of no-deal Brexit|date=13 March 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183742/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-tariffs-idUKKBN1QU1J9|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-no-deal-tariff-wto-trade-eu-theresa-may-northern-ireland-a8825076.html|title=EU says UK no-deal Brexit tariff plan is 'illegal'|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019|website=The Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329185317/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-no-deal-tariff-wto-trade-eu-theresa-may-northern-ireland-a8825076.html|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Litigation===\nThere has been litigation to explore the constitutional footings on which Brexit stands after ''[[R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]'' (simply known as the \"Miller case\") and the 2017 Notification Act:\n* In ''R. (Webster) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union'', a [[Divisional court (England and Wales)|Divisional Court]] of [[Peter Gross (judge)|Gross LJ]] and [[Nicholas Green (judge)|Green MR]] determined that the substantive decision to leave the EU that was notified on 29 March 2017 was in fact the executive decision of the Prime Minister using a statutory power of decision found to have been delegated to her by the Notification Act: this is confirmed by the [[House of Commons Library]] commentary on the case.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Vaughne|last2=Mars|first2=Sylvia de|date=1 November 2019|title=Brexit questions in national and EU courts|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8415|journal=|access-date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200119084822/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8415|archive-date=19 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The case was appealed to the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.crowdjustice.com/case/a50-chall-her-e50/|title=Article 50 Challenge|work=CrowdJustice|access-date=20 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522112547/https://www.crowdjustice.com/case/a50-chall-her-e50/|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and paragraph 15 of the judgement, along with the citable nature of the decision were upheld.  While the case was criticised academically by a PhD candidate,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2018/06/26/robert-craig-new-article-50-case-resoundingly-rejected-by-the-divisional-court/|title=Robert Craig: New Article 50 Case Resoundingly Rejected by the Divisional Court|date=26 June 2018|work=UK Constitutional Law Association|access-date=20 November 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708132234/https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2018/06/26/robert-craig-new-article-50-case-resoundingly-rejected-by-the-divisional-court/|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> aspects of the case's analysis were supported by the [[UK Supreme Court]] in [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|Miller 2]] at paragraph 57, which confirmed that:\n\n<blockquote>\"Parliament, and in particular the House of Commons as the democratically elected representatives of the people, has a right to have a voice in how that change comes about is indisputable.</blockquote>\n* This confirmation that the decision was an executive act was part of the basis of [[R (Wilson) v Prime Minister|''R.'' (''Wilson) v. Prime Minister'']]<ref>'Grounds for Judicial Review' in ''Wilson v Prime Minister'', 13 August 2018.[http://www.croftsolicitors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/239484-Grounds-for-Judicial-Review-and-Statement-of-Facts.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825212619/http://www.croftsolicitors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/239484-Grounds-for-Judicial-Review-and-Statement-of-Facts.pdf |date=25 August 2018 }}</ref> which allied this point with the concerns about the irregularities in the referendum.  The High Court hearing was on 7 December 2018 before [[Duncan Ouseley|Ouseley MJ]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukineuchallenge.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Bremain-mailer-021118-UKEU-edit-website.pdf|title=UKEU Challenge Update|last=|first=|date=|website=UKEU Challenge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401210410/https://www.ukineuchallenge.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Bremain-mailer-021118-UKEU-edit-website.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> and when judgement was given it was held that: courts\u2019 job was not to rule on irregularities in the \u2018leave\u2019 campaign as these were not questions of law; it was also said that the case was brought both too early and too late.<ref name=\"Miller\"/> Judgement in the Court of Appeal (before [[Gary Hickinbottom|Hickinbottom LJ]] and [[Charles Haddon-Cave|Haddon-Cave LJ]]) before also went against the applicant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.uk/publications/wilson-others-v-the-prime-minister-respondent-1-and-the-electoral-commission-respondent-2/|title=Wilson & others \u2013v- The Prime Minister (Respondent 1) and The Electoral Commission (Respondent 2)|website=www.judiciary.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330073014/https://www.judiciary.uk/publications/wilson-others-v-the-prime-minister-respondent-1-and-the-electoral-commission-respondent-2/|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Regarding the reversibility of a notification under Article 50, ''Wightman and others v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union'' was referred to Court of Justice of the European Union;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/21/triggering-article-50-reversed-european-court-justice-brexit-bad-dream|title=Today's ruling shows the triggering of article 50 can be reversed|last=Maugham|first=Jolyon|date=21 September 2018|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=20 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401210405/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/21/triggering-article-50-reversed-european-court-justice-brexit-bad-dream|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the UK government sought to block this referral, taking the matter on appeal to the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|UK Supreme Court]], but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/reasons-for-the-determination-in-the-matter-of-secretary-of-state-for-exiting-the-european-union-v-wightman-and-others.pdf|title=Reasons for the determination in the matter of Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union (Appellant) v Wightman and others (Respondents)|last=UK Supreme Court|date=|website=UK Supreme Court|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120221031/https://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/reasons-for-the-determination-in-the-matter-of-secretary-of-state-for-exiting-the-european-union-v-wightman-and-others.pdf|archive-date=20 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> On 10 December 2018, the [[Court of Justice of the European Union|Court of Justice of the EU]] ruled that the UK could unilaterally revoke its Article 50 notification.<ref>{{cite web|title=The United Kingdom is free to revoke unilaterally the notification of its intention to withdraw from the EU.|url=https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/upload/docs/application/pdf/2018-12/cp180191en.pdf|publisher=Court of Justice of the European Union|accessdate=18 January 2019|date=10 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612165315/https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/upload/docs/application/pdf/2018-12/cp180191en.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{Main|Impact of Brexit}}\n\nMany effects of Brexit depended on whether the UK left with a [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]], or before an agreement was ratified ([[No-deal Brexit|\"no-deal\" Brexit]]).<ref name=\"What is a 'no deal' Brexit?\">{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/brexit/no-deal-brexit-what-meaning-uk-leave-uk-consequences/|title=What is a no-deal Brexit? Here are the consequences of the UK leaving the EU without a deal|date=4 September 2019|website=inews.co.uk|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610235916/https://inews.co.uk/news/brexit/no-deal-brexit-what-meaning-uk-leave-uk-consequences/|archive-date=10 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Financial Times'' said that there were approximately 759 international agreements, spanning 168 non-EU countries, that the UK would no longer have been a party to upon leaving the EU.<ref name=\"FTAfter\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f1435a8e-372b-11e7-bce4-9023f8c0fd2e|title=After Brexit: the UK will need to renegotiate at least 759 treaties|last1=McClean|first1=Paul|date=30 May 2017|work=Financial Times|accessdate=31 May 2017|quote=Through analysis of the EU treaty database, the FT found 759 separate EU bilateral agreements with potential relevance to Britain, covering trade in nuclear goods, customs, fisheries, trade, transport and regulatory co-operation in areas such as antitrust or financial services. This includes multilateral agreements based on consensus, where Britain must re-approach 132 separate parties. Around 110 separate opt-in accords at the UN and World Trade Organization are excluded from the estimates, as are narrow agreements on the environment, health, research and science. Some additional UK bilateral deals, outside the EU framework, may also need to be revised because they make reference to EU law. Some of the 759 are so essential that it would be unthinkable to operate without them. Air services agreements allow British aeroplanes to land in America, Canada or Israel; nuclear accords permit the trade in spare parts and fuel for Britain's power stations. Both these sectors are excluded from trade negotiations and must be addressed separately.|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531162500/https://www.ft.com/content/f1435a8e-372b-11e7-bce4-9023f8c0fd2e|archive-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:The Border on Killeen School Road - geograph.org.uk - 446719.jpg|thumb|Border crossing at Killeen (near [[Newry]]), marked only by a speed limit in km/h (Northern Ireland uses mph).]]\n\nEconomists expect that Brexit will have damaging [[Economic effects of Brexit|immediate and longer term effects]] on the economies of the UK and at least part of the EU27. In particular, there is a broad consensus among economists and in the economic literature that Brexit will likely reduce the UK's real per capita income in the medium and long term, and that the Brexit referendum itself damaged the economy.{{#tag:ref|See:<ref name=\"NYT Feel Good\"/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"auto8\"/><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\":10\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/><ref name=\"auto11\"/><ref name=\":12mitchell\"/><ref name=\"auto12\"/><ref name=\"auto13\"/>|group=lower-alpha}}<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/brexit-everyone-loses-britain-loses-most|title=Brexit: Everyone Loses, but Britain Loses the Most|date=1 March 2019|website=PIIE|language=en|access-date=17 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091244/https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/brexit-everyone-loses-britain-loses-most|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/european-economic-experts-panel|title=Question C: Leaving the European Union without a trade agreement would have a large negative impact on the UK economy.|last=|first=|date=|website=www.igmchicago.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723063822/http://www.igmchicago.org/european-economic-experts-panel|archive-date=23 July 2019|access-date=21 December 2019}}</ref> Studies found that Brexit-induced uncertainty reduced British GDP, British national income, investment by business, employment and British international trade from June 2016 onwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/impact-brexit-uncertainty-uk-exports|title=The impact of Brexit uncertainty on UK exports|last=Crowley|first=Meredith|last2=Exton|first2=Oliver|date=21 January 2019|website=VoxEU.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708142203/https://voxeu.org/article/impact-brexit-uncertainty-uk-exports|archive-date=8 July 2019|access-date=21 January 2019|last3=Han|first3=Lu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cepr.org/active/publications/discussion_papers/dp.php?dpno=13446|title=DP13446 Renegotiation of Trade Agreements and Firm Exporting Decisions: Evidence from the Impact of Brexit on UK Exports|last=|first=|date=|website=cepr.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329195055/https://cepr.org/active/publications/discussion_papers/dp.php?dpno=13446|archive-date=29 March 2019|access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Graziano|first=Alejandro|last2=Handley|first2=Kyle|last3=Lim\u00e3o|first3=Nuno|date=2018|title=Brexit Uncertainty and Trade Disintegration|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w25334|journal=|volume=|pages=|doi=10.3386/w25334|access-date=21 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421114507/https://www.nber.org/papers/w25334|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/brexit-has-already-hurt-eu-and-non-eu-exports-by-up-to-13-new-research-105334|title=Brexit has already hurt EU and non-EU exports by up to 13% \u2013 new research|last=Soegaard|first=Christian|work=The Conversation|access-date=5 November 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105202912/https://theconversation.com/brexit-has-already-hurt-eu-and-non-eu-exports-by-up-to-13-new-research-105334|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Douch|first=Mustapha|last2=Edwards|first2=T. Huw|last3=Soegaard|first3=Christian|date=2018|title=The Trade Effects of the Brexit Announcement Shock|url=https://ideas.repec.org/p/wrk/warwec/1176.html|url-status=dead|journal=|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106004634/https://ideas.repec.org/p/wrk/warwec/1176.html|archive-date=6 November 2018|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/consequences-brexit-uk-inflation-and-living-standards-first-evidence?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter|title=The Brexit vote and inflation \u2013 updated evidence|last=Breinlich|first=Holger|last2=Leromain|first2=Elsa|date=2020-03-02|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=2020-03-02|last3=Novy|first3=Dennis|last4=Sampson|first4=Thomas}}</ref> A 2019 analysis found that British firms substantially increased [[offshoring]] to the EU after the Brexit referendum, whereas European firms reduced new investments in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/brexit-and-outward-investment-uk-firms|title=Voting with their money: Brexit and outward investment by UK firms|last=Breinlich|first=Holger|last2=Leromain|first2=Elsa|date=12 February 2019|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=13 February 2019|last3=Novy|first3=Dennis|last4=Sampson|first4=Thomas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212120115/https://voxeu.org/article/brexit-and-outward-investment-uk-firms|archive-date=12 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-investment-idUKKCN1Q003D|title=Brexit referendum spurs British companies into investing in EU|date=11 February 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=13 February 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213124128/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-investment-idUKKCN1Q003D|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK government's own Brexit analysis, leaked in January 2018, showed that UK economic growth would be stunted by 2\u20138% over the 15 years following Brexit, the amount depending on the leave scenario.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/albertonardelli/the-governments-own-brexit-analysis-says-the-uk-will-be|title=The Government's Own Brexit Analysis Says The UK Will Be Worse Off in Every Scenario Outside The EU|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=30 January 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129235752/https://www.buzzfeed.com/albertonardelli/the-governments-own-brexit-analysis-says-the-uk-will-be|archive-date=29 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b3d35136-0543-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Secret data show Britain worse off under all Brexit scenarios|website=Financial Times|access-date=30 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904210201/https://www.ft.com/content/b3d35136-0543-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Economists warned that London's future as an international financial centre depended on passport agreements with the EU.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eichengreen|first=Barry|date=7 January 2019|title=The international financial implications of Brexit|journal=International Economics and Economic Policy|language=en|volume=16|pages=37\u201350|doi=10.1007/s10368-018-0422-x|issn=1612-4812|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/5d39b74066994b07894717fecc61ce5fbacfd813}}</ref><ref name=\":25\">{{Cite journal|last=Armour|first=John|date=1 March 2017|title=Brexit and financial services|journal=Oxford Review of Economic Policy|volume=33|issue=suppl_1|pages=S54\u2013S69|doi=10.1093/oxrep/grx014|issn=0266-903X}}</ref> Pro-Brexit activists and politicians have argued for negotiating trade and migration agreements with the \"[[CANZUK]]\" countries\u2014those of [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and the [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/13/canzuk-after-brexit-canada-australia-new-zealand-and-britain-can/|title=CANZUK: after Brexit, Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Britain can unite as a pillar of Western civilisation|author=Andrew Roberts|date=13 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114034026/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/13/canzuk-after-brexit-canada-australia-new-zealand-and-britain-can/|archive-date=14 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/columnist/2016/06/24/brexit-boosts-canzuk-replacement-european-union-column/86347818/|title=Brexit boosts 'CANZUK' replacement for European Union: Column|author=James C. Bennett|date=24 June 2016|work=USA Today|accessdate=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725124317/https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/columnist/2016/06/24/brexit-boosts-canzuk-replacement-european-union-column/86347818/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2014but economists have noted that trade deals with those countries would be far less valuable to the UK than EU membership.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/opinion/brexit-meets-gravity.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Brexit Meets Gravity|last=Krugman|first=Paul|date=10 July 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 January 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023457/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/opinion/brexit-meets-gravity.html|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/brexit/2018/08/21/can-brexit-defy-gravity-right-now-it-is-still-much-cheaper-to-trade-with-neighbouring-countries/|title=Long read: Can Brexit defy gravity? It is still much cheaper to trade with neighbouring countries|last=21 August|last2=2018{{!}}#LSEThinks|date=21 August 2018|website=LSE BREXIT|language=en-US|access-date=14 January 2019|last3=Brexit|first3=Economics of|last4=Comments|first4=Featured{{!}}7|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023228/http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/brexit/2018/08/21/can-brexit-defy-gravity-right-now-it-is-still-much-cheaper-to-trade-with-neighbouring-countries/|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/how-economists-brexit-manage-defy-laws-gravity|title=How 'Economists for Brexit' manage to defy the laws of gravity|last=Sampson|first=Thomas|last2=Dhingra|first2=Swati|date=2 June 2016|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=14 January 2019|last3=Ottaviano|first3=Gianmarco|last4=Reenen|first4=John Van|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023300/https://voxeu.org/article/how-economists-brexit-manage-defy-laws-gravity|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Studies indicate that Brexit will exacerbate regional economic inequality in the UK, as already struggling regions will be hardest hit by Brexit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carter|first=Andrew|last2=Swinney|first2=Paul|year=2019|title=Brexit and the Future of the UK's Unbalanced Economic Geography|url=|journal=The Political Quarterly|language=en|volume=0|pages=72\u201383|doi=10.1111/1467-923X.12649|issn=1467-923X|quote=What all of these studies agree on is that whichever Brexit deal is struck, even the most advantageous will have a negative impact on future economic growth for all places across the UK in the short to medium term. And they also agree that over the longer term its places that are already struggling that are likely to struggle the most, further exacerbating the country's unbalanced economic geography.}}</ref>\n\nThe potential [[Brexit and the Irish border|impact on the border]] between [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]] has been a contentious issue. Since 2005, [[Republic of Ireland\u2013United Kingdom border|the border]] has been essentially invisible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-what-are-the-options-for-the-irish-border-after-brexit|title=FactCheck: What are the options for the Irish border after Brexit?|work=Channel4.com|date=|accessdate=25 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914121956/https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-what-are-the-options-for-the-irish-border-after-brexit|archive-date=14 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After Brexit, it will be the only UK\u2013EU land border.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brexit will not mean hard border, leaders vow|url-access=registration|date=31 January 2017|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brexit-will-not-mean-hard-border-leaders-vow-83c7lzs80|work=[[The Times, Ireland edition]]|first=Niamh|last=Lyons|accessdate=29 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131070359/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brexit-will-not-mean-hard-border-leaders-vow-83c7lzs80|archive-date=31 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> All involved parties agree a hard border should be avoided,<ref>{{cite news|work=The Irish Times|date=26 July 2016|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-may-not-impact-common-travel-area-expert-claims-1.2711557|accessdate=12 October 2016|title=Britain does not want return to Northern Ireland border controls, says May|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012155040/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-may-not-impact-common-travel-area-expert-claims-1.2711557|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> as it might compromise the [[Good Friday Agreement]] that ended the [[The Troubles|Northern Ireland conflict]].<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/opinions/20-years-good-friday-agreement-northern-ireland-nic-r-intl/index.html Brexit: the unexpected threat to peace in Northern Ireland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614050104/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/opinions/20-years-good-friday-agreement-northern-ireland-nic-r-intl/index.html |date=14 June 2018 }} Nic Robertson, [[CNN]], 6 April 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/george-mitchell-uk-and-ireland-need-to-realise-whats-at-stake-in-brexit-talks-36785893.html George Mitchell: UK and Ireland need to realise what's at stake in Brexit talks.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172607/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/george-mitchell-uk-and-ireland-need-to-realise-whats-at-stake-in-brexit-talks-36785893.html |date=29 March 2019 }} ''[[Belfast Telegraph]]'', 8 April 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/brexit-threatens-good-friday-agreement-irish-pm-warns Brexit threatens Good Friday agreement, Irish PM warns.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731012207/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/brexit-threatens-good-friday-agreement-irish-pm-warns |date=31 July 2018 }} David Smith, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 March 2018</ref> To forestall this, the EU proposed a [[Irish backstop|\"backstop agreement\"]] (the Northern Ireland Protocol) that would have kept the UK in the Customs Union and kept Northern Ireland in some aspects of the Single Market also, until a lasting solution was found.<ref name=\"BBC backstop\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44615404|title=Brexit: What are the backstop options?|work=BBC News|date=13 September 2019|access-date=24 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725040206/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44615404|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The backstop was part of the withdrawal agreement, but was replaced in the revised agreement.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBrexit [[Impact of Brexit on the European Union|caused the European Union]] to lose its second-largest economy, its third-most populous country,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merkur.de/politik/brexit-folgen-fuer-deutschland-und-eu-zr-6489983.html|title=EU-Austritt des UK: Diese Folgen hat der Brexit f\u00fcr Deutschland und die EU|date=22 August 2016|work=[[M\u00fcnchner Merkur|Merkur.de]]|language=German|trans-title=UK Exit from EU: Brexit has these consequences for Germany and the EU|accessdate=30 November 2016|quote=Die Briten haben sich f\u00fcr einen Abschied entschieden, Europa wird nun anders aussehen. Der Kontinent verliert seine (neben Frankreich) st\u00e4rkste Milit\u00e4rmacht samt Atomwaffenarsenal, seine zweitgr\u00f6\u00dfte Volkswirtschaft, das Land mit der drittgr\u00f6\u00dften Bev\u00f6lkerung, die Finanzhauptstadt der Welt und einen von zwei Pl\u00e4tzen im UN-Sicherheitsrat. [The British have decided to leave. Europe will now look different. The continent will be losing its strongest military power (alongside France),{{nbsp}}... its second largest economy, the country with the third largest population, the financial capital of the world, and one of two seats on the UN Security Council.]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209172124/http://www.merkur.de/politik/brexit-folgen-fuer-deutschland-und-eu-zr-6489983.html|archive-date=9 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and the second-largest net contributor to the EU budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/eurokrise/deutschland-zahlt-am-meisten-in-den-eu-haushalt-14378202.html|title=EU-Haushalt: Deutschland \u00fcberweist das meiste Geld an Br\u00fcssel|last=Hendrik Kafsack|date=8 August 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|accessdate=9 October 2016|language=German|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009105442/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/eurokrise/deutschland-zahlt-am-meisten-in-den-eu-haushalt-14378202.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Brexit will result in an additional financial burden for the remaining net contributors, unless the budget is reduced accordingly. The UK will no longer be a shareholder in the [[European Investment Bank]], where it has 16% of the shares.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftspolitik/nettozahler-zum-eu-haushalt-brexit-wird-teuer-fuer-deutschland-14429116.html|title=Brexit wird teuer f\u00fcr Deutschland|publisher=Reuters/[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]]|date=10 September 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|accessdate=9 October 2016|language=German|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009105443/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftspolitik/nettozahler-zum-eu-haushalt-brexit-wird-teuer-fuer-deutschland-14429116.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Analyses indicate that the departure of the relatively economically liberal UK will reduce the ability of remaining economically liberal countries to block measures in the [[Council of the European Union|Council of the EU]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huhe|first=Narisong|last2=Naurin|first2=Daniel|last3=Thomson|first3=Robert|title=Don't cry for me Britannia: The resilience of the European Union to Brexit|journal=European Union Politics|volume=21|language=en|page=1465116519882096|doi=10.1177/1465116519882096|issn=1465-1165|url=https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/69935/1/Huhe_etal_EUP_2019_the_resilience_of_the_European_Union_to_Brexit.pdf|year=2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://carnegieeurope.eu/2018/03/23/there-is-life-for-eu-after-brexit-pub-75876|title=There Is Life for the EU After Brexit|last=Gruyter|first=Caroline de|date=|website=Carnegie Europe|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205060756/https://carnegieeurope.eu/2018/03/23/there-is-life-for-eu-after-brexit-pub-75876|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> In 2019, ahead of Brexit, the [[European Medicines Agency]] and [[European Banking Authority]] moved their headquarters from London to [[Amsterdam]] and [[Paris]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/ema-now-operating-amsterdam|title=EMA now operating from Amsterdam|publisher=European Medicines Agency|date=March 11, 2019|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016015945/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/ema-now-operating-amsterdam|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/ema-gets-keys-to-new-hq|work=[[The Pharma Letter]]|date=November 18, 2019|title=EMA gets keys to new HQ|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203032720/https://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/ema-gets-keys-to-new-hq|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20190605/european-bank-regulator-arrives-in-paris-in-boost-to-macrons-financial-vision-for-city|title=European bank regulator arrives in Paris in boost to Macron's financial vision for city|date=June 5, 2019|work=The Local|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203032718/https://www.thelocal.fr/20190605/european-bank-regulator-arrives-in-paris-in-boost-to-macrons-financial-vision-for-city|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Brexit, the UK will leave the [[Common Agricultural Policy]] (CAP),<ref name=\"CAP payments\">[https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/brexit/legislation/farm-payments-in-a-no-deal-brexit/ Farm payments in a 'no deal' Brexit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930210303/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/brexit/legislation/farm-payments-in-a-no-deal-brexit/ |date=30 September 2019 }}. [[House of Commons Library]]. 15 August 2019.</ref> which provides government financial support to farmers in the EU.<ref name=\"CAP\">[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-agricultural-policy Common Agricultural Policy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906173554/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-agricultural-policy |date=6 September 2019 }}. [[Institute for Government]].</ref> The UK receives much less than it contributes.<ref name=\"CAP\" /> Brexit allows the UK to develop its own agriculture policy.<ref name=\"UK agriculture policy\">[https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8218 Brexit: UK agriculture policy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930210306/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8218 |date=30 September 2019 }}. [[House of Commons Library]]. 11 September 2018.</ref> The current UK government has committed to maintaining the same payments to farmers until the end of the current parliament, even without a withdrawal agreement.<ref name=\"CAP payments\" /> The Agriculture Bill is intended to replace the CAP with a new system.<ref name=\"UK agriculture policy\" /> The UK will also leave the [[Common Fisheries Policy]] (CFP)<ref name=\"fisheries briefing\">[http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8396/CBP-8396.pdf Briefing Paper: Fisheries and Brexit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809162431/https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8396/CBP-8396.pdf |date=9 August 2019 }}. [[House of Commons Library]]. 5 September 2019.</ref> that lets all EU countries fish within 12 nautical miles of the UK coast<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36358016 \"Reality Check: How would Brexit affect the UK's fishing waters?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001015505/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36358016 |date=1 October 2019 }}. BBC News. 31 May 2016.</ref> and lets the EU set catch quotas.<ref name=\"CFP explainer\">[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-fisheries-policy Common Fisheries Policy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518094241/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-fisheries-policy |date=18 May 2019 }}. [[Institute for Government]].</ref> The combined EU fishing fleets land about six million tonnes of fish per year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/documentation/publications/pcp_en.pdf|title=Main world producers (2007)|date=|accessdate=23 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812111024/http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/documentation/publications/pcp_en.pdf|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> about half of which are from UK waters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/15/uk-fishermen-may-not-win-waters-back-after-brexit-eu-memo-reveals|title=UK fishermen may not win waters back after Brexit, EU memo reveals|author=Daniel Boffey|date=15 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=3 July 2017|location=London|quote=Source: House of Lords, NAFC Marine Centre, University of the Highlands and Islands.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702131533/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/15/uk-fishermen-may-not-win-waters-back-after-brexit-eu-memo-reveals|archive-date=2 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> By leaving the CFP, the UK could develop its own fisheries policy.<ref name=\"CFP explainer\" /> The UK will also leave the [[London Fisheries Convention]] that lets Irish, French, Belgian, Dutch and German vessels fish within six nautical miles of the UK's coast.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40471466 \"UK to withdraw from international fishing arrangement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910072536/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40471466 |date=10 September 2019 }}. BBC News. 2 July 2017.</ref>\n[[File:Gibraltar Customs side of the Spain-Gibraltar frontier, Winston Churchill Avenue, Gibraltar.jpg|thumb|Cars crossing into Gibraltar clearing customs formalities. Gibraltar is outside the customs union, VAT area, and [[Schengen Zone]].]]\n\n[[Gibraltar]], a [[British Overseas Territory]] bordering Spain, will be [[Effect of Brexit on Gibraltar|affected by Brexit]]. Spain asserts a [[Status of Gibraltar|territorial claim on Gibraltar]]. After the referendum, Spain's Foreign Minister renewed calls for joint Spanish\u2013British control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36618796|title=Brexit: Spain calls for joint control of Gibraltar|work=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626055917/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36618796|archive-date=26 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In late 2018, the British and Spanish governments agreed that any dispute over Gibraltar would not affect Brexit negotiations,<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/uk-spain-reach-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar-spanish-pm/article/534934|title=UK, Spain reach Brexit deal over Gibraltar: Spanish PM|date=18 October 2018|work=Digital Journal|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328153315/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/uk-spain-reach-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar-spanish-pm/article/534934|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the British government agreed that UK\u2013EU treaties made after Brexit would not automatically apply to Gibraltar.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/spanish-pm-lifts-effective-veto-on-brexit-deal-after-gibraltar-guarantee-1.3709604 \"Spanish PM lifts effective veto on Brexit deal after Gibraltar 'guarantee'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125152747/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/spanish-pm-lifts-effective-veto-on-brexit-deal-after-gibraltar-guarantee-1.3709604 |date=25 November 2018 }}. ''The Irish Times''. 24 November 2018.</ref>\n\nBrexit poses challenges to British academia and research, as the UK is likely to lose research funding from EU sources; see a reduction in students from the EU; find it harder to hire researchers from the EU; and UK students will find it harder to study abroad in the EU.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Mayhew|first=Ken|date=1 March 2017|title=UK higher education and Brexit|journal=Oxford Review of Economic Policy|volume=33|issue=suppl_1|pages=S155\u2013S161|doi=10.1093/oxrep/grx012|issn=0266-903X}}</ref> The UK is currently a member of the [[European Research Area]] and likely to wish to remain an associated member following Brexit.<ref>\"It is likely that the UK would wish to remain an associated member of the European Research Area, like Norway and Iceland, in order to continue participating in the EU framework programmes.\"{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|title=UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030|publisher=UNESCO Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-92-3-100129-1|location=Paris|page=269|quote=|access-date=20 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630025557/http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|archive-date=30 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK government has guaranteed funding for research currently funded by EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/13/philip-hammond-treasury-to-guarantee-post-brexit-funding-for-eu-backed-projects|title=Treasury to guarantee post-Brexit funding for EU-backed projects|first1=Jessica|last1=Elgot|first2=Larry|last2=Elliott|first3=Nicola|last3=Davis|date=13 August 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=14 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414164358/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/13/philip-hammond-treasury-to-guarantee-post-brexit-funding-for-eu-backed-projects|archive-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAn early 2019 study found that Brexit would deplete the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) workforce, create uncertainties regarding care for British nationals living in the EU, and put at risk access to vaccines, equipment, and medicines.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite journal|last=McKee|first=Martin|last2=Galsworthy|first2=Mike|last3=Stuckler|first3=David|last4=Jarman|first4=Holly|last5=Greer|first5=Scott|last6=Hervey|first6=Tamara|last7=Fahy|first7=Nick|date=25 February 2019|title=How will Brexit affect health services in the UK? An updated evaluation|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/b4d421286023c78a03c4bd25468eedeb00203954|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=0|issue=10174|pages=949\u2013958|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30425-8|issn=0140-6736|pmid=30819519}}</ref> The [[Department of Health and Social Care]] has said it has taken steps to ensure the continuity of medical supplies after Brexit.<ref>[https://www.england.nhs.uk/eu-exit/medicines/ Continuity of supplies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212005859/https://www.england.nhs.uk/eu-exit/medicines/ |date=12 December 2019 }}. [[NHS England]].</ref>  The number of non-British EU nurses registering with the NHS fell from 1,304 in July 2016 to 46 in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jun/12/96-drop-in-eu-nurses-registering-to-work-in-britain-since-brexit-vote|title=96% drop in EU nurses registering to work in Britain since Brexit vote|last=Siddique|first=Haroon|date=12 June 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402084706/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jun/12/96-drop-in-eu-nurses-registering-to-work-in-britain-since-brexit-vote|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Brexit, the UK will have the final say over the laws that govern it.<ref>[https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8133 The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill: Supremacy and the Court of Justice] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930205721/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8133 |date=30 September 2019 }}. [[House of Commons Library]], 8 November 2017.</ref> Under the ''[[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]]'', EU laws will no longer have [[Primacy of European Union law|supremacy over]] UK laws after Brexit.<ref name=\"withdrawal bill\">[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/pdfs/ukpgaen_20180016_en.pdf Explanatory notes on the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930205726/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/pdfs/ukpgaen_20180016_en.pdf |date=30 September 2019 }}. [[The Stationery Office]]. pp.4, 8</ref> To maintain continuity, the Act converts EU law into UK law as \"retained EU law\". After Brexit, the British parliament (and the devolved legislatures) can decide which elements of that law to keep, amend or repeal.<ref name=\"withdrawal bill\"/> Furthermore, UK courts will no longer be bound by the judgments of the [[Court of Justice of the European Union|EU Court of Justice]] after Brexit.\n\nAfter Brexit, the UK would be able to control immigration from the EU and [[European Economic Area|EEA]],<ref>[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/publications/managing-migration-after-brexit Managing migration after Brexit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929223849/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/publications/managing-migration-after-brexit |date=29 September 2019 }}. [[Institute for Government]]. 8 March 2019.</ref> as it can end EU [[freedom of movement]]. The current UK government intends to replace it with a new system. The government's 2018 [[white paper]] proposes a \"skills-based immigration system\" that prioritizes skilled migrants. EU and EEA citizens already living in the UK can continue living there after Brexit by applying to the EU Settlement Scheme, which began in March 2019. Irish citizens will not have to apply to the scheme.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/19/the-post-brexit-immigration-plans-at-a-glance \"The post-Brexit immigration plans at a glance\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726214731/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/19/the-post-brexit-immigration-plans-at-a-glance |date=26 July 2019 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 19 December 2018.</ref><ref>[https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8584 Briefing Paper: EU Settlement Scheme] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929223839/https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8584 |date=29 September 2019 }}. [[House of Commons Library]]. 19 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-uks-future-skills-based-immigration-system/future-skills-based-immigration-system-executive-summary Future skills-based immigration system: executive summary] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929223835/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-uks-future-skills-based-immigration-system/future-skills-based-immigration-system-executive-summary |date=29 September 2019 }}. [[Home Office]]. 19 December 2018.</ref> Studies estimate that Brexit and the end of free movement will likely result in a large decline in immigration from EEA countries to the UK.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Forte|first=Giuseppe|last2=Portes|first2=Jonathan|date=1 May 2017|title=Macroeconomic Determinants of International Migration to the UK|location=Rochester, NY|ssrn=2979949}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Portes|first=Jonathan|date=1 November 2016|title=Immigration after Brexit|journal=National Institute Economic Review|volume=238|issue=1|pages=R13\u2013R21|doi=10.1177/002795011623800111|issn=0027-9501}}</ref> After Brexit, any foreigner wanting to do so more than temporarily could need a work permit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46038799|title=Brexit: What effect could leaving the European Union have on football transfers?|date=31 October 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112051235/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46038799|archive-date=12 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/how-brexit-will-affect-premier-league-football/cwp6p3hhmuxx119cm1syhwyi2|title=How Brexit will affect Premier League football|date=22 March 2019|website=Goal.com|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112145957/https://www.goal.com/en/news/how-brexit-will-affect-premier-league-football/cwp6p3hhmuxx119cm1syhwyi2|archive-date=12 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy leaving the EU, the UK would leave the [[European Common Aviation Area]] (ECAA), a [[single market]] in commercial air travel,<ref name=\"Aviation-IFG\">[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/european-common-aviation-area-brexit Aviation and the European Common Aviation Area (ECAA)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930210000/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/european-common-aviation-area-brexit |date=30 September 2019 }}. [[Institute for Government]]. 10 September 2017.</ref> but could negotiate a number of different future relationships with the EU.<ref name=\"Aviation-IFG\" /> UK airlines would still have permission to operate within the EU with no restrictions, and vice-versa. The UK government seeks continued participation in the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA).<ref name=\"Aviation-IFG\" /> The UK has its own [[Air transport agreement|air service agreements]] with 111 countries, which permit flights to-and-from the country, and further 17 countries through its EU membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal|title=Flights to and from the UK if there's no Brexit deal|date=24 September 2018|work=Government of the United Kingdom|accessdate=9 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210152535/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal|archive-date=10 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These have since been replaced. Ferries will continue, but with obstacles such as customs checks.<ref name=\"atclogistics\">{{cite web|url=https://www.atc-logistics.ie/getting-to-europe-post-brexit-the-impact-on-ferry-companies/|title=Getting to Europe Post Brexit \u2013 The Impact on Ferry Companies|date=23 April 2018|website=Atc-logistics.ie|access-date=22 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323004211/https://www.atc-logistics.ie/getting-to-europe-post-brexit-the-impact-on-ferry-companies/|archive-date=23 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> New ferry departures between the Republic of Ireland and the European mainland have been established.<ref name=\"atclogistics\" />\n\nConcerns have been raised that Brexit might create security problems for the UK, particularly in law enforcement and counter-terrorism where the UK could use the EU's databases on individuals crossing the British border.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/why-brexit-may-be-good-for-terrorists-and-the-kremlin-and-bad-for-european-security/2018/12/24/b3ec2462-020a-11e9-958c-0a601226ff6b_story.html|title=Why Brexit may be good for terrorists and the Kremlin and bad for European security|last=|first=|date=2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115234413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/why-brexit-may-be-good-for-terrorists-and-the-kremlin-and-bad-for-european-security/2018/12/24/b3ec2462-020a-11e9-958c-0a601226ff6b_story.html|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\n{{Main|Brexit in popular culture}}\n[[File:Brexit-is-a-monstrosity-float-2017-10-01-in-manchester-photo-robert-mandel.jpg|thumb|Anti-Brexit protesters in [[Manchester]]]]\n[[File:DBG 22473 (26370830218).jpg|thumb|[[D\u00fcsseldorf]] carnival parade in February 2018]]\n\nBrexit has inspired many creative works, such as murals, sculptures, novels, plays, movies and video games. The response of British artists and writers to Brexit has in general been negative, reflecting a reported overwhelming percentage of people involved in Britain's [[creative industries]] voting against leaving the European Union.<ref>Mia Jankowicz, \"Britain's thriving art scene strangled by Brexit chaos\" in ''Politics.co.uk,'' 20 March 2017: [http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/03/20/britain-s-thriving-art-scene-strangled-by-brexit-chaos Online Link] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924114435/http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/03/20/britain-s-thriving-art-scene-strangled-by-brexit-chaos |date=24 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|European Union|Modern history|Politics|United Kingdom}}\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Brexit\n |3=Brexit, Article 50, and other articles\n |5=Britain, Ireland and the European Union}}\n* [[Danish withdrawal from the European Union|Danexit]]\n* [[Dutch withdrawal from the European Union]]\n* [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill 2019\u201320]]\n* [[Frexit]]\n* [[Greek withdrawal from the eurozone]]\n* [[European Single Market#Integration of non-EU states|Integration of non-EU states]]\n* [[International reactions to the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]\n* [[Multi-speed Europe]]\n* [[R (Factortame Ltd) v Secretary of State for Transport#House of Lords|Interpretation of EU Treaty law by European Court of Justice]]\n* [[Opposition to Brexit in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Referendums related to the European Union]]\n* [[Withdrawal of Greenland from the European Communities]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n* Ansorg, N. & Haastrup, T.: \"Brexit Beyond the UK's Borders: What It Means for Africa\", [https://www.giga-hamburg.de/en/publication/brexit-beyond-the-uks-borders-what-it-means-for-africa GIGA Focus Afrika No. 03/2016]\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Clarke|first1=Harold D.|last2=Goodwin|first2=Matthew|author2link=Matthew Goodwin|last3=Whiteley|first3=Paul|title=Brexit: Why Britain Voted to Leave the European Union|date=2017|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-1316605042}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Culkin|first1=Nigel|last2=Simmons|first2=Richard|title=Tales of Brexits Past and Present: Understanding the Choices, Threats and Opportunities In Our Separation from the EU|date=2018|publisher=Emerald Publishing|location=Bingley|isbn=978-1787694385}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Geoffrey|authorlink=Geoff Evans (political scientist)|last2=Menon|first2=Anand|author2link=Anand Menon|title=Brexit and British Politics|date=2017|publisher=[[Polity Press]]|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-1509523863}}\n\n* [[Jonathan Freedland|Freedland, Jonathan]], \"Fools Rush Out\", ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', vol. LXVI, no. 14 (26 September 2019), pp.&nbsp;30, 32, 34\u201335.\n\n* {{cite journal|last=Hobolt|first=Sara B.|authorlink=Sara Hobolt|date=7 September 2016|title=The Brexit vote: a divided nation, a divided continent|journal=[[Journal of European Public Policy]]|volume=23|issue=9|pages=1259\u20131277|doi=10.1080/13501763.2016.1225785|issn=1350-1763|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/67546/7/Hobolt_The%20Brexit%20vote%20a%20divided%20.pdf}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Oliver|first1=Tim|authorlink=Tim Oliver|title=Understanding Brexit: A concise introduction|date=2018|publisher=[[Policy Press]]|location=Bristol|isbn=978-1447346395}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=O'Rourke|first1=Kevin|authorlink=Kevin O'Rourke|title=A Short History of Brexit: From Brentry to Backstop|date=2019|publisher=Pelican|location=London|isbn=978-0241398272}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=O'Toole|first1=Fintan|authorlink=Fintan O'Toole|title=Heroic Failure: Brexit and the Politics of Pain|date=2018|publisher=Apollo|location=London|isbn=978-1789540987}}\n\n* Outhwaite, William (ed.) 2017). ''Brexit: Sociological Responses''. London: Anthem Press, {{ISBN|978-1783086443}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Peers|first1=Steve|authorlink=Steve Peers|title=The Brexit: The Legal Framework for Withdrawal from the EU or Renegotiation of EU Membership|date=2016|publisher=[[Hart Publishing]]|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84946-874-9|oclc=917161408}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Rogers|first1=Ivan|authorlink=Ivan Rogers|title=9 Lessons in Brexit|date=2019|publisher=Short Books|location=London|isbn=978-1780723990}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=Brexit |c=Category:Brexit |commonscat= |n=yes |q=no |s=Consolidated version of the Treaty on European Union/Title VI: Final Provisions#Article 50 |author=no |b=no |v=Brexit |d=Q7888194}}\n* [https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2019-20/earlyparliamentarygeneralelection.html Early Parliamentary General Election Bill 2019-20, Progress in Parliament]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/brexit UK government's Brexit information]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/article-50-and-negotiations-with-the-eu UK government's official negotiation documents]\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/unitedkingdom/en/brexitpublic/brexitstudies.html European Parliament \u2013 Brexit impact studies]\n* [https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/761852/05_December-_EU_Exit_Attorney_General_s_legal_advice_to_Cabinet_on_the_Wi