{"title_page": "\u017dor\u017es Tikmers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{MedalTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Rowing at the Summer Olympics|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| the {{URS}} }}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Moscow]]|[[Rowing at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxed four|Coxed four]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''\u017dor\u017es Tikmers''' (born 22 January 1957 in [[Iecava]], [[Latvian SSR]]) is a [[Latvia]]n former [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who competed for the [[Soviet Union]] in the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].\n\nIn 1980 he was a crew member of the Soviet boat which won the silver medal in the [[coxed four]]s event.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ti/zorzs-tikmers-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tikmers, Zorzs}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Iecava]]\n[[Category:Latvian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Soviet male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Latvian Academy of Sport Education alumni]]\n\n\n{{USSR-rowing-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Latvia-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{MedalTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Rowing at the Summer Olympics|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| the {{URS}} }}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Moscow]]|[[Rowing at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxed four|Coxed four]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''\u017dor\u017es Tikmers''' (born 22 January 1957 in [[Iecava]], [[Latvian SSR]]) is a [[Latvia]]n former [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who competed for the [[Soviet Union]] in the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].\n\nIn 1980 he was a crew member of the Soviet boat which won the silver medal in the coxed fours event.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ti/zorzs-tikmers-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tikmers, Zorzs}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Iecava]]\n[[Category:Latvian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Soviet male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Latvian Academy of Sport Education alumni]]\n\n\n{{USSR-rowing-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Latvia-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kaamis007", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%BDor%C5%BEs_Tikmers"}
{"title_page": "WSFX-TV", "text_new": "{{short description|Fox affiliate in Wilmington, North Carolina}}\n{{Infobox broadcast \n| call_letters             = WSFX-TV\n| station_logo             = [[File:Wsfx 2009.png|150px]]\n| station_slogan           = \n| station_branding         = Fox Wilmington ''(general)''<br>''[[WECT]] News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| analog                   = \n| digital                  = 29 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 26 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| other_chs                = \n| subchannels              = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''26.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (1994\u2013present)|'''26.2:''' [Blank] \u2192 [[Court TV]] (soon)|'''26.3:''' [[Grit (TV network)|Grit]]|'''26.4:''' [[Ion Television]]}}\n| founded                  = \n| airdate                  = {{Start date and age|1984|09|24|p=y}}\n| location                 = [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n| country                  = United States\n| callsign_meaning         = '''W'''e're '''S'''uper '''F'''o'''X'''<br>(former branding)\n| former_callsigns         = WJKA (1984\u20131994)\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''[[analog television|Analog]]:'''<br>26 (UHF, 1984\u20132008)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>30 (UHF, until 2020)<br>'''''Translator:'''<br>19 W19CA [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]]''\n| owner                    = {{nowrap|[[American Spirit Media]], [[Limited liability company|LLC]]}}\n| licensee                 = WSFX License Subsidiary, LLC\n| operator                 = [[Gray Television]]<br>''(via [[shared services|SSA]])''\n| sister_stations          = [[WECT]], [[WMBF-TV]], [[WBTV]] ([[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]])\n| former_affiliations      = '''Analog/DT1:'''<br>[[CBS]] (1984\u20131994)<br>'''DT2:'''<br>[[This TV]] (until 2020)\n| effective_radiated_power = 200 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|590|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 72871\n| class                    = [[digital terrestrial television|DT]]\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|34|7|54|N|78|11|16|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://foxwilmington.revrocket.us/}}\n}}\n\n'''WSFX-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 26 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 29), is a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Wilmington, North Carolina|Wilmington]], [[North Carolina]], United States and serving the [[Cape Fear (region)|Cape Fear region]]. The station is owned by [[American Spirit Media]]; [[Gray Television]], which owns [[NBC]] affiliate [[WECT]] (channel 6), operates WSFX-TV under a [[shared services]] agreement (SSA). The two outlets share studios on [[U.S. Route 117|Shipyard Boulevard]] in Wilmington and transmitter facilities near [[Winnabow, North Carolina]]. On [[cable television|cable]], WSFX-TV is available on [[Spectrum (cable service)|Charter Spectrum]] channel 9.\n\n==History==\n[[File:WECT and WSFX Headquarters.jpg|thumb|left|WECT and WSFX headquarters in Wilmington, North Carolina]]\nThe station signed-on [[1984 in television|September 24, 1984]] as '''WJKA''', a [[CBS]] affiliate. It aired an [[analog television|analog]] signal on UHF channel 26 leasing space on the tower of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WWAY]] in [[unincorporated area#United States|unincorporated]] Brunswick County. The station was originally owned by Wilmington Telecasters, a company owned by [[Robinson O. Everett|Robinson]] and Katherine Everett of [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]]. The station originally operated from studios located at 1926 Oleander Drive/[[U.S. Route 76 in North Carolina|US 76]] in Wilmington. \n\nPrior to WJKA's start-up, Wilmington was one of the few [[media market|markets]] in the United States without its own CBS affiliate and one of the few in the [[Eastern Time Zone]] without full network service. Future sister station WECT had a secondary CBS affiliation until [[cable television|cable]] arrived in the area in the 1970s while [[Florence, South Carolina]]'s [[WBTW]] covered most of the market with a Grade B signal. From the 1970s until WJKA's sign-on, most local cable systems in the market carried [[Greenville, North Carolina|Greenville]] affiliate [[WNCT-TV]] or WBTW while [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] affiliate [[WTVD]] (now an ABC owned-and-operated station) was carried by some cable providers.\n\nChannel 26's tenure as a CBS affiliate was far from successful. The station operated on a shoestring budget. It mostly served as a \"pass-through\" for automated CBS programming, and produced almost no local content. The fact that WNCT and WBTW provided at least Grade B coverage to some parts of the market did not help matters either. Further complicating matters, Raleigh's [[WRAL-TV]] (now an NBC affiliate), which had been available on cable in Wilmington for decades, switched from ABC to CBS a year after WJKA's sign-on. This move forced the fledgling station to compete against three of the strongest CBS affiliates in the [[Southeastern United States]]. Under those circumstances, WJKA barely registered as a blip in the local [[Nielsen ratings]] against rivals WECT and WWAY.\n\nIn 1994, WJKA along with sister station [[KECY-TV]] in [[El Centro, California]]\u2013[[Yuma, Arizona]] [[1994\u20131996 United States broadcast TV realignment|switched their affiliations to Fox]]; while this occurred shortly after [[NFL on CBS|CBS]] lost broadcasting rights of the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[National Football Conference]] to [[Fox NFL|Fox]] and before the [[1995 Carolina Panthers season|inaugural season]] of the [[Carolina Panthers]] the following year, the change followed several disputes between Robinson O. Everett and CBS (including one over a planned upgrade of KECY's [[KDFX-CD|translator]] in [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]] to a full-power station).<ref name=v-wjkafox>{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Joe|title=CBS loses trio of affils to Fox|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR120188/?refcatid=14|accessdate=January 16, 2013|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 14, 1994}}</ref> On September 18, channel 26 changed its call letters to the current '''WSFX-TV'''.\n\n[[File:WSFX.jpg|thumb|Fox Wilmington logo on side of studio building]]\n\nBefore the switch, Wilmington was the only portion of North Carolina (and one of the few in the Eastern Time Zone) without an over-the-air Fox affiliate of its own. Until this point in time, the area's cable systems piped in the national [[Foxnet]] service or [[WLFL]] in Raleigh. As a result of WSFX's affiliation switch, Wilmington did not have an over-the-air CBS affiliate until March 2000 when [[low-power broadcasting#Television|low-powered]] [[UPN]] affiliate [[WILM-LD|WILM-LP]] switched its primary affiliation to CBS. During that time, cable systems supplemented the area with either WRAL, WNCT, or WBTW.\n\nOn paper, the loss of CBS should have put channel 26 in serious jeopardy. Fox had just begun airing a full week's worth of programming just a season earlier, but then as now, does not produce any daytime programming. WSFX thus now faced having to buy an additional 10 hours of programming per day. However, the move to Fox rejuvenated the station. Its main competition was now WLFL. Within a few years, it was one of the strongest small-market Fox affiliates in the country. Until 1996, WSFX also doubled as the Fox affiliate for the Florence\u2013[[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]] market which did not have its own affiliate (some cable systems in the Myrtle Beach area imported [[WACH]] from [[Columbia, South Carolina]] prior to WSFX's switch to Fox). In fact, the current call letters stand for '''S'''uper'''F'''o'''X''', referring to its on-air name at the time and relatively wide coverage area. Since the station's over-the-air signal does not reach Florence, the [[Pee Dee]] area had to rely on cable for Fox programming until WGSE-TV (now [[WFXB]]) in Myrtle Beach took the affiliation.\n\nIn 2003, Everett sold the station to Southeastern Media Holdings. [[Raycom Media]] then took over WSFX's operations through a shared service agreement with WECT. As part of the agreement, WSFX's operations were integrated into WECT's facility. In the late-1990s, [[Time Warner Cable]] in Lumberton began to drop Wilmington stations. This station was dropped from cable in [[Laurinburg, North Carolina|Laurinburg]] in the early to mid-1990s when it was still a CBS affiliate. WFXB is currently the only Fox affiliate offered on cable in that area. On June 27, 2011, WSFX was re-branded as \"Fox Wilmington\" and introduced a new logo. Besides sharing the same call letters, this television station and [[non-commercial educational]] radio station [[WSFX (FM)|WSFX-FM]] 89.1 in [[Nanticoke, Pennsylvania]] have no other relation to each other.\n\nOn May 8, 2008, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) announced five stations in Wilmington (including WSFX) had agreed to voluntarily cease analog broadcasting on September 8. The Wilmington market was billed as the first in the nation to convert to all-digital transmissions due to its role as the FCC's digital transition test market. [[Hawaii]] shut down analog broadcasting in January 2009 followed by more but not all full-power television broadcasters on February 17, 2009.\n\n==Digital channels==\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! [[Video resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio|Aspect]]\n! PSIP short name\n! Programming <ref>http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WSFX#station</ref>\n|-\n| 26.1 \n| [[720p]] \n| [[16:9]] \n| WSFX-DT \n| Main WSFX-TV programming / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n|-\n| 26.2 \n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[480i]] \n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[4:3]] \n| Court TV \n| [[Court TV]]\n|-\n| 26.3 \n| Grit \n| [[Grit (TV network)|Grit]]                         \n|-\n| 26.4 \n| Ion \n| [[Ion Television]]\n|-\n| 26.5\n| Dabl\n| [[Dabl]]\n|}\n\n==Defunct translator==\nWSFX formerly operated an analog [[broadcast relay station#Broadcast translators|translator]], '''W19CA''' channel 19, that was licensed to [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]] and had a transmitter in [[Lumber Bridge, North Carolina|Lumber Bridge]]. The northern and western areas of [[Robeson County, North Carolina|Robeson County]] ([[St. Pauls, North Carolina|St. Pauls]], [[Parkton, North Carolina|Parkton]], and [[Red Springs, North Carolina|Red Springs]]) also do not carry WSFX even though its translator was located in Lumber Bridge. The repeater had a directional signal covering Robeson County fairly well and could also be seen as far north as [[Raeford, North Carolina|Raeford]] in [[Hoke County, North Carolina|Hoke County]] and [[Hope Mills, North Carolina|Hope Mills]] in [[Cumberland County, North Carolina|Cumberland County]] in the Raleigh/Durham market.\n\n==Programming==\n[[television syndication|Syndicated]] programming on WSFX includes ''[[Maury (talk show)|Maury]]'', ''[[Modern Family]]'', ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', and ''[[Family Feud]]'' among others.\n\n==News operation==\n[[File:WECT and WSFX.jpg|thumb|The WECT and WSFX shared studio in Wilmington, North Carolina]]\nAs WJKA, the station had virtually no news department for most of its tenure as a CBS affiliate. In the mid-1980s, it did air a weekday noon show called ''Midday'' offering local news headlines and entertainment reports. In the early-1990s, WJKA actually operated a short-lived news department branded as ''WJKA [[Action News]] 26''. It attempted to create another source for newscasts besides longtime dominant WECT and runner up WWAY. Despite the efforts of WJKA and WWAY, WECT maintained a strong lead in the market ratings and viewership counts by consistently holding the top spot in Nielsen marks.\n\nOn September 22, 2003 through a new share agreement, WECT began producing a nightly half-hour prime time newscast on WSFX called ''Fox 26 News at 10'' (now ''Fox Wilmington News at 10''). This was eventually joined by an sixty-minute extension of WECT's weekday morning show on September 13, 2006 called ''Carolina in the Morning on Fox 26'' (now ''Carolina in the Morning on Fox Wilmington''), currently airing from 7 until 8 on WSFX offering an alternative to the national morning shows seen on the market's [[Big Three television networks|big three network]]-affiliated stations. On August 31, 2008, WECT became Wilmington's first television outlet to upgrade local news production to high definition level and the broadcasts on WSFX were included in the change. \n\nAt some point in time, WECT added a third newscast to WSFX called ''Fox 26 News at 6:30'' (later became ''Fox Wilmington News at 6:30''), which only aired on weeknights and attempted to compete against the [[ABC World News Tonight|national]] [[CBS Evening News|evening]] [[NBC Nightly News|newscasts]] seen on the big three networks. It would be canceled by the end of 2013 in preparation to expand the weeknight edition of the 10 o'clock show to an hour (which occurred on January 15, 2014). On September 6, 2016, WSFX premiered a 7 p.m. newscast. After WWAY stopped producing weekend evening newscasts on August 1, 2009, WECT and WSFX became the only outlets in Wilmington to offer evening broadcasts seen seven nights a week. Although WWAY eventually reintroduced a local newscast airing Sunday nights at 11, WECT and WSFX remain the only channels in the market to air newscasts throughout the weekend. \n\nWSFX currently airs 13\u00bd hours of news produced by sister station WECT. All newscasts on WSFX air from WECT's primary set but with modified [[duratrans]] indicating the Fox-branded shows.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://foxwilmington.revrocket.us}}\n*[http://wilmington.thistv.com/ WSFX-DT2 This TV]\n*[https://www.wect.com/ WECT]\n*{{TVQ|WSFX-TV}}\n\n{{Wilmington TV}}\n{{Fox North Carolina}}\n{{Gray TV}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wsfx-Tv}}\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Wilmington, North Carolina|SFX-TV]]\n[[Category:Fox network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Ion Television subchannel-only affiliates]]\n[[Category:Grit (TV network) affiliates]]\n[[Category:Gray Television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fox affiliate in Wilmington, North Carolina}}\n{{Infobox broadcast \n| call_letters             = WSFX-TV\n| station_logo             = [[File:Wsfx 2009.png|150px]]\n| station_slogan           = \n| station_branding         = Fox Wilmington ''(general)''<br>''[[WECT]] News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| analog                   = \n| digital                  = 29 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 26 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| other_chs                = \n| subchannels              = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''26.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (1994\u2013present)|'''26.2:''' [Blank] \u2192 [[Court TV]] (soon)|'''26.3:''' [[Grit (TV network)|Grit]]|'''26.4:''' [[Ion Television]]}}\n| founded                  = \n| airdate                  = {{Start date and age|1984|09|24|p=y}}\n| location                 = [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n| country                  = United States\n| callsign_meaning         = '''W'''e're '''S'''uper '''F'''o'''X'''<br>(former branding)\n| former_callsigns         = WJKA (1984\u20131994)\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''[[analog television|Analog]]:'''<br>26 (UHF, 1984\u20132008)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>30 (UHF, until 2020)<br>'''''Translator:'''<br>19 W19CA [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]]''\n| owner                    = {{nowra